[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Greetings to all again! Welcome to the second part of my course featuring the Open Sicilian.    As in the first part of this course, you can expect to find here a lot of novelties, new ideas and surprises that will make your opponents not know what they are doing!   All, of course, backed up by correspondence games and last generation engines to make it as objectively correct as possible so that you will never have any kind of problem in case your opponent magically knows everything!   In fact, I am already anticipating that if our opponents want to come close to equality they will have to be experts in their lines and be able to solve a lot of problems over the board! All this will also ensure us a good time advantage to start the game.    Again I have chosen lines with similar ideas and positions understandable and simple to play to assimilate the concepts and ideas little by little until you become a real expert in them. Thanks to some specific move orders that I recommend in some lines, we will even have the ability to switch between several options, thus giving us a double repertoire.    In this part of the course we are going to focus on the ...e6 Sicilians -Taimanov, Two Knights, Kan, Sheveningen and sidelines- and the ...g6 Sicilians -Dragon, Accelerated Dragon, Hyperaccelerated Dragon, and sidelines-. I am sure you will enjoy the course a lot and score a lot of points in your games with it @@@StartBracket@@myself and some Grandmasters that I help with their opening preparation are already testing the lines with great results@@@EndBracket@@. I hope you enjoy this second part on my course, and see you there! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Taimanov 6.a3 with 7.Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this part of the course we will analyze the ...e6-Sicilians, in which Black keeps the flexibility of their piece development, as we are going to see. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ This is one of the most flexible move orders for Black, as it allows them to choose between the Taimanov Sicilian, the Two Knights Sicilian and it allows playing with ...a6 as well. As this move hits the center directly, it is not easy for White to go for a Maroczy Bind structure directly.   At this point I am going to recommend two moves. The first one -our main line- will be Nc3, which is the standard move. Our idea is to develop our pieces and control the center. However, the party is not over yet. The second move I recommend goes specifically against opponents who have the Taimanov as a main weapon, since we are practically going to make life impossible for them.. }
5. Nc3
{ The knight develops naturally and conyrols some central squares. After this move, our chances of going for a Marozcy structure are gone. However, this will not be a problem.   5.a3!  is the other option and will be analyzed in the Two Knights chapter. }
5... Qc7
{ After this move we are in Taimanov Sicilian territory. This is -in my humble opinion- the best Sicilian for Black after the Najdorf and the Sveshnikov. Black usually plays very flexible by combining pawn pushes on both flanks @@StartBracket@@...a6 and ...b5 or ...h5@@EndBracket@@. As Black's queen controls the e5-square, they does not need to play ...d6 in many lines and, as a result, the f8-bishop can be developed to a more aggresive squares such as b4, c5 or even d6 in some cases. }
6. a3
{ This will be my recommendation against the Taimanov. As I did in Play the Sicilian, Part 1, I am going to try to recommend positions with similar pawn structures. This is the reason why we are going to play the move a3 in quite a number of lines. Being less well-known than the main line, this move -played by strong Russian GMs- is the most flexible move by White here and its idea is to pre-empt Black plans with ...a6+...b5 and prevent their dark-squared bishop to get to b4. }
6... Be7
{ In this order Black tries to delay momentarily the development of the g8-knight in order to be able to act in a more flexible way in the face of pawn advances on the kingside. }
7. Be3
{ Continuing our standard development, keeping all our options still open. }
7... a6
{ Continuing to play ambiguously is quite interesting, as Black prepares the typical queenside expansion. Several Taimanov experts have played this line as Black, especially Indian players -including our Chessable friend Harikrishna. }
8. g4
{ Gaining some space quicly on the kingside, taking advantage of the fact that Black is now ready to react in the center with ...d5. This move also prevents the development of the knight on g8, as our idea is to bring our pawn to g5. }
8... b5
{ Black ignores our g-pawn advance and keeps on creating counterplay on the queenside.   8...Nf6  9.g5  Ng8  10.h4  . }
9. Nxc6
{ This move is usually stronger after Black plays ...b5. In general, the best ways to take on c6 are either with the b-pawn -in order to achieve the ...d5 break to open the b-file- or with the bishop, with the idea to exert some pressure along the diagonal and clear the b-file or push ...a5+...b4. Having played ...b5, Black cannot get back to these two ideas anymore. }
9... Qxc6
{ This way of taking on c6 is usually not dangerous at all because the queen is now very exposed and stops controlling the important e5-square. }
10. g5 { Preventing the g8-knight's jumps. } 10... h6
{ Black manages to remove our g5-pawn from the board but, in return, the g-file will be open and the knight will remain in the very passive h6-square.   10...Bb7  11.Qd4  . }
11. gxh6 Nxh6 12. Rg1
{ Exerting pressure on the semi-open g-file and, at the same time, putting an eye on g4 to be able to continue with Qd2 without worrying about Black's ...Ng4 ideas. }
*

