[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Two Knights Alternatives #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. a3
{ When I discovered this move, I could not resist recommending it. It is designed specifically against Taimanov players @@StartBracket@@the best continuation here is ...Nf6 and, after Nc3, we will transpose directly to the Two Knights with a3@@@EndBracket@@. However, most Taimanov players will have no idea of that position and will try to transpose to what they know with ...Qc7, after which they will get a nasty surprise. }
5... d5
{ It makes sense for Black to try to open the position because the move a3 does not immediately fight for the center. However, it is not entirely true because the move a3 controls b4 and, therefore, Nc3 will be stronger. }
6. exd5 exd5 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. Be3
{ We keep on developing naturally. In this case, the point is to go for vO-O-O to put immediate pressure against d5. }
8... Ng4 { 8...Bd6  9.Qd2  O-O  10.O-O-O  Same plan: going for f3+g4 and Kb1. }
9. Bb5 { Black is not developed enough to afford to play this type of moves. }
9... Nxe3 { 9...Bd7  does not get in time due to  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Bxc6  . }
10. fxe3 Bd7 11. Qh5
{ Black is not in time to defend against all threats and their house is falling. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Two Knights Main Line #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. a3
{ When I discovered this move, I could not resist recommending it. It is designed specifically against Taimanov players @@StartBracket@@the best continuation here is ...Nf6 and, after Nc3, we will transpose directly to the Two Knights with a3@@@EndBracket@@. However, most Taimanov players will have no idea of that position and will try to transpose to what they know with ...Qc7, after which they will get a nasty surprise. }
5... Nf6
{ The most concrete move, after which we will directly transpose to the standard lines after Nc3. }
6. Nc3 Be7
{ Playing this move is not as easy if our opponents do not know it beforehand, as it allows Nxc6+e5. Therefore, I think we will face d6 more often over the board. }
7. Nxc6
{ 7.Be3  is also a possible and interesting option, but we cannot go for the h3 idea because Black can play ...d5 in one move. }
7... bxc6 8. e5 Nd5 9. Qg4
{ With the idea of either creating weaknesses quickly or force Black to lose the right to castle. At the same time, we develop our pieces with tempo. }
9... g6 10. Bd2
{ This is my recommendation. This move deviates from the most played ones, but our point is just developing the bishop with the idea of taking on c3 with this piece and prepare to go O-O-O. }
10... Qc7
{ Natural; however, the queen is not particularly well placed in this square since it puts itself in range of a recapture on e5 as we are going to see. }
11. Qg3 d6 { 11...O-O?  12.O-O-O  . } 12. Nxd5 cxd5
{ After  12...exd5  13.Bf4  we can clearly see why the queen is not ideal on c7: it cannot recapture. }
13. Bc3
{ Closing the c-file, defending b2 and eyeing at Black's short castle. We want to play moves such as h4. }
13... O-O 14. O-O-O
{ The bishop pair on d3-e3 defends and attacks in perfect harmony. Now all that is missing is to push Harry -the h-pawn- and our position will be perfect. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Two Knights Main Line #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. a3
{ When I discovered this move, I could not resist recommending it. It is designed specifically against Taimanov players @@StartBracket@@the best continuation here is ...Nf6 and, after Nc3, we will transpose directly to the Two Knights with a3@@@EndBracket@@. However, most Taimanov players will have no idea of that position and will try to transpose to what they know with ...Qc7, after which they will get a nasty surprise. }
5... Nf6
{ The most concrete move, after which we will directly transpose to the standard lines after Nc3. }
6. Nc3 d6
{ It makes much sense to control the e5-square directly, but this loses the possibility of playing ...d5 in one move. Let's take advantage of it. }
7. Be3 Be7 8. h3
{ This is my recommendation, and a way of playing that can be seen in other Sicilian move orders. However, this move has been played in only two amateur games. Logically, we want to play g4 and we also keep the flexibility with our king, which we could bring either to the kingside or to the queenside.   8.g4?!  is premature due to  8...Nxd4!  9.Qxd4  e5  10.Qa4+  Bd7  11.Bb5  Nxg4  . }
8... O-O 9. g4 { Following our logical idea. } 9... d5
{ This is one of the most natural continuations. However, as Black has already lost a tempo with ...d6, this move is not so strong now. }
10. Bg2 { Bringing the bishop to the diagonal that is about to open up. } 10...
Ne5
{ Black wants to jump to c4 now that our bishop does not control it anymore.   10...Nxd4  11.Qxd4  developing  11...dxe4  12.O-O-O  with a nice advantage for White thanks to the fact that our pieces are active. }
11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. O-O
{ After this we get to an isolated pawn structure where Black has some problems to finish the development since the bishop on c8 lacks good squares and the pawn on d5 is weak. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4...Nc6 & 5...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 a6
{ One of the fashionable Sicilians, recently played by Rapport in the Candidates Tournament as well as by Andreikin and Nepo on numerous occasions. }
6. Bf4
{ White controls some key squares as Black's queen is not on c7 yet. Now e5 will always be an option after ...Nf6.   6.a3!?  it seems difficult for Black to avoid transposing to the other lines we have studied in this course after this move. However, I think it is good to know another extra option. }
6... d6
{ The main move, controlling e5 to be able to develop the knight to f6 comfortably. }
7. Nxc6
{ Going for this type of structure as neither the pawn on d6 nor the pawn on a6 are particularly useful here. }
7... bxc6 8. h4
{ Winning space and giving the g5-square to the bishop and h3 to the rook. }
8... e5 9. Bg5 Nf6
{ After  9...f6?!  10.Be3  the pawn occupies the natural square of the knight and now it is very difficult for Black to finish their development. }
10. Bc4
{ Taking advantage that the diagonal that has been weakened after ...e5. }
10... h6
{ A difficult move to make taking into account the fact that it creates a breaking point and weakens even the light squares even more.   The move  10...Rb8  is only a tempo loss because ...Rxb2 is still not a threat as the rook will be trapped after Bb3  11.Qd3  . }
11. Bxf6
{ I know it hurts to give up the bishop. Believe me, it hurts much more to me. In this case, the point is that Black will have no pawn breaks available thanks to their weak light squares. However, we can improve our position comfortably. }
11... Qxf6 12. Qe2
{ Going for O-O-O. We put the queen on e2 pto defend f2 and free the d3-square to be able to bring the rook to the attack at some point. }
12... Be7
{ 12...g6?!  has no sense because the bishop will not be able to develop by fianchetto due to the fact that d6 is weak.  13.O-O-O   12...Be6?!  13.Bxa6  . }
13. O-O-O O-O 14. Kb1
{ After this move we reach a very comfortable position. However, Black has almost no active plans due to the fact that our tight control of their pawn breaks. On the other hand, we have aggressive plans at our disposal such as g4+g5, opening everything up. }
*

