[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Scheveningen #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6
{ Entering the Sicilian Scheveningen. Black controls the e5-push and prepares a future queenside expansion. }
6. g4
{ As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the drawback of ...d6 by Black is that it is not possible to play the only pawn break available -...d5- in one move. We also take advantage that, unlike in the Najdorf, now we can make g4 indeed, since the bishop on c8 does not control g4 due to the fact that there is a pawn on e6.    Given the rasons above, my recommendation is to play g4 at this point. Black's best plan in most cases is to break with ...d5 at some point, but with the ...d6-tempo down. }
6... h6
{ Black should not allow g5. The problem of this move is that In the long term it will be difficult for Black to castle short since there is a break point on the g5-square, which will make it very easy for us to access to our opponent's castling. }
7. Rg1
{ Defending quickly the g4-pawn to prevent tactical tricks and preparing an eventual break on g5. This rook move is also useful in some lines, where White can play Bg2 after Black's pawn break on d5 and the subsequent trades. }
7... Nc6 { 7...Be7  8.Be3  Nc6  . } 8. Be3 Be7 9. a3
{ The quintessential move of the course! Once again, this waiting move is very useful, as Black has to decide how to arrange their pieces.   ...O-O would be too risky, as we have the attack well prepared; ...Bd7 would reduce the strength of the d5-break; and the natural a6 is a mistake, as we are going to see. }
9... a6
{ 9...O-O  10.h4  Black has to keep the king in the center, otherwise it will end up in so much trouble. }
10. h4 d5
{ The logical move, but we are quite well developed to fave this break adequately.   10...h5  a typical reaction. However, we already have the rook on g1, which is very well placed in case the g-file opens up.  11.gxh5!  Nxh5  12.Be2  We want to castle queenside. Black's king will not be safe anymore. }
11. Qe2
{ Exploiting our development to the maximum. We want to castle quenside in order to to hassle the queen on the d-file. }
11... Nxe4
{ This would be logical to decrease the strenght of our g5-push, but it doesn't solve anything.   If  11...dxe4  12.O-O-O!  our rook is on the open d-file  12...Qc7  13.Nxc6  Qxc6  14.Bg2  and White will play g5 and e4 falls. }
12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. O-O-O { The same idea. The queen has to move. } 13... Qc7 14.
Nxc6 Qxc6 15. Bd4
{ Again the development advantage is overwhelming. We attack g7 and Ag2 is coming. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Scheveningen #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6
{ Entering the Sicilian Scheveningen. Black controls the e5-push and prepares a future queenside expansion. }
6. g4
{ As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the drawback of ...d6 by Black is that it is not possible to play the only pawn break available -...d5- in one move. We also take advantage that, unlike in the Najdorf, now we can make g4 indeed, since the bishop on c8 does not control g4 due to the fact that there is a pawn on e6.    Given the rasons above, my recommendation is to play g4 at this point. Black's best plan in most cases is to break with ...d5 at some point, but with the ...d6-tempo down. }
6... e5
{ A very direct move. The drawback is that it weakens the surrounding light squares. }
7. Nf5 h5
{ 7...Nc6  8.Bg5  .   7...g6  8.Ne3  the knights are on perfect squares to control d5 and we can also continue with a quick g5 to kick away the only defender of that square. }
8. Bg5 { We keep developing our pieces aiming to fight for the light squares. }
8... hxg4 { 8...Nxe4  . } 9. Nd5 Bxf5
{ 9...Be6  10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.Qxg4  we have two strong knights and, besides, Black's king is in the center, which is too much for our opponent to handle. }
10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. exf5 Bh6
{ The idea is following with ...Bg5, then bring the king to g7 via f8 and support the pawn with a move like ...Rh4. The key plan for us here is to prevent Black's setup.   11...Nc6?!  12.c3!  controlling the black knight's key squares.  12...Bh6  13.Qxg4  . }
12. h4
{ Preventing BLack to build a solid setup and uncoordinating their pieces. }
12... gxh3
{ If  12...Kf8  13.Rg1  we recapture on g4 with the rook, activating one more piece.   12...Nc6  13.Bg2  . }
13. Rxh3 Kf8 14. Qf3
{ White has a dominant position thanks to the pin on the h-file. Bd3 and c3 are coming next. }
*

