1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ In this chapter we will have a look at some Black sidelines that BLack has at their disposal in this position. Objectively, they are not dangerous for us, but it is important to know them because they contain some hidden traps. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Qb6
{ A tricky -and important to know!- variation.   5...a6?  6.e5!  Black should react somehow to prevent this.  6...Ng8  7.Bf4  and White has good development without giving anything in return for it. }
6. e5 { The move that we almost always play if Black allows it. } 6... Bc5 7.
Ndb5
{ Aiming quickly at the dark squares. It's hard to leave the f2-pawn in the air, but Black will get nowhere by taking it, as their pieces will be uncoordinated. }
7... Bxf2+ 8. Ke2 { Black lacks pieces to create threats. } 8... Ng4
{ 8...Nd5  9.Nd6+  Ke7  10.Nxd5+  . } 9. h3 Nxe5 10. Qd6
{ We are threatening Nc7 and Qxe5 and Black has no adequate answer against it. }
10... Nbc6 11. Nc7+ Kd8 12. Bg5+ f6 13. Nxe6+ Ke8 14. Nxg7+
{ The f6-falls as well as Black's position. } *

