[Black "Accelerated Dragon #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ After this move we enter directly in the Accelerated Dragon. In return of giving up the center, Black will have a solid control of the central dark squares. }
5. c4
{ Going into a Maroczy Bind structure. White gains space in the center and takes advantage of it. We have to be a bit careful on the next moves, as Black may have some tactical tricks at their disposal. }
5... Bg7 6. Be3
{ It is important to not take on c6 because this will help Black's development. Although the b2-pawn is hanging -which can be scary-, Black has no way of exploiting it. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 Ng4
{ An old line. Black aims to trade some pieces, but keeping more contro, of the dark squares. The problem is that the c6-knight will will disrupt Black's own pieces even more. }
8. Qxg4 Nxd4 9. Qd1 Nc6
{ This move order is not dangerous for us. We will continue our standard development with a big advantage. }
10. Qd2 d6 11. Rc1 O-O 12. Be2 Be6 13. O-O
{ We have finished our development. We will bring our rooks to the center and the knight to d5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Accelerated Dragon #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ After this move we enter directly in the Accelerated Dragon. In return of giving up the center, Black will have a solid control of the central dark squares. }
5. c4
{ Going into a Maroczy Bind structure. White gains space in the center and takes advantage of it. We have to be a bit careful on the next moves, as Black may have some tactical tricks at their disposal. }
5... Nf6
{ One of the trickiest move orders. The f6-knight has the chance of jumping to g4 in some lines. }
6. Nc3 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 d6
{ It is important to control the e5-square.   If  7...Bg7?  8.e5!  and the knight has no good squares to go to and has to return home.  8...Ng8  9.Bf4  cwith a huge development advantage for White. This is a good example of what can happen to Black if they are not careful with the e5 advance in this type of positions. }
8. Be3 { We keep on developing our pieces in a standard way. } 8... Bg7 9. Be2
{ Controlling g4 and getting ready to castle on the kingside. } 9... O-O
{ Si  9...Qa5  10.O-O  O-O  11.Qd3!  .   10.Qd3?  we have to be careful!  10...Nxe4!  and, suddenly, all Black's pieces are perfectly coordinated. This is a very typical trap and we should be very careful to not allow it. }
10. Qd3
{ A trendy move. From d3 we defend e4 more effectively, as we do not weaken our position with f3 and our plan will be faster than Black's to carry out. }
10... Be6 11. Bd4
{ Also possibke is  11.O-O  but I think the text move is more flexible. } 11...
Nd7 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. O-O a5 14. b3
{ We continue our typical plan, once we have stopped Black's counterplay based on ...a4.   If  14.Rad1?!  a4!  Black gets the a5-square for their pieces and c4 is looser. }
*

