[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Classical Dragon #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3
{ Controlling g4 to prevent knight jumps there and, besides, aiming to play for the g4-push ourselves. }
7... Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O
{ 8...Bd7?!  is inaccurate, as the queen does not put pressure anymore along the d-file. Therefore, it is not necessary to  to be so aware of the d5-break and, for that reason, we can skip the move Ac4.  9.g4  O-O  10.O-O-O  .   8...d5?  9.Bb5!  Bd7  10.Nxd5  . }
9. Bc4
{ This move is important because it controls d5. In addition, the bishop can serve as a defensive piece once we bring it to b3. }
9... Nd7
{ A very old line. Black maneuvers with the knights to try to gain quick access to the c4-square. The problem with this is that Black's castling without the knight on f6 is barely holding and the c4-square can be covered with b3. }
10. h4
{ Directly to the neck, taking advantage of the fact that the knight does not control h5 anymore. }
10... Nb6 11. Be2
{ The simplest move, with the idea of covering the c4-square very easily: simply playing b3. }
11... Ne5 12. b3 { Black's whole plan vanishes with this simple move. } 12...
d5 { 12...h5  13.O-O-O  preparing Bh6 and g4, cracking the position open. } 13.
f4 Ng4 14. e5
{ Blocking the bishop's diagonal and keeping our attack alive with h5. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Taimanov 6.a3 Nf6"]
[Black "Taimanov Attempt 4...Qc7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qc7
{ This move order is sometimes played by some Taimanov players to transpose to the main line but avoiding some particular variations. }
5. Be3
{ This precise move order will force BLack to enter an inferior variation of the Taimanov Sicilian. The point of not comitting the knight to c3 yet is keeping the c2-c4 possibility open.   5.Nc3  e6  6.a3  . }
5... Nf6
{ 5...a6  6.c4  White generally plays the Maroczy only when Black plays the move ...a6.   5...e6  6.a3!  transposing. }
6. Nc3
{ Black will have to play ...e6 sooner or later if they want to transpose. }
6... Nxd4
{ The only attempt to avoid the transposition. However, this trade has no justification, as it creates some weaknesses.   6...e6  7.a3  .   6...a6  7.a3!  insisting!  7...e6  . }
7. Qxd4
{ When the queen is on d1, we almost always take with this piece to accelerate our development. }
7... e5 8. Qa4
{ It is important to control b4 to prevent Black's annoying pin. } 8... a6
{ 8...Be7  9.O-O-O  . } 9. Bg5
{ Fighting against the main defender of the d5-square. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Taimanov 6.a3 Nf6"]
[Black "6.a3 Nf6 7.Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this part of the course we will analyze the ...e6-Sicilians, in which Black keeps the flexibility of their piece development, as we are going to see. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ This is one of the most flexible move orders for Black, as it allows them to choose between the Taimanov Sicilian, the Two Knights Sicilian and it allows playing with ...a6 as well. As this move hits the center directly, it is not easy for White to go for a Maroczy Bind structure directly.   At this point I am going to recommend two moves. The first one -our main line- will be Nc3, which is the standard move. Our idea is to develop our pieces and control the center. However, the party is not over yet. The second move I recommend goes specifically against opponents who have the Taimanov as a main weapon, since we are practically going to make life impossible for them.. }
5. Nc3
{ The knight develops naturally and conyrols some central squares. After this move, our chances of going for a Marozcy structure are gone. However, this will not be a problem.   5.a3!  is the other option and will be analyzed in the Two Knights chapter. }
5... Qc7
{ After this move we are in Taimanov Sicilian territory. This is -in my humble opinion- the best Sicilian for Black after the Najdorf and the Sveshnikov. Black usually plays very flexible by combining pawn pushes on both flanks @@StartBracket@@...a6 and ...b5 or ...h5@@EndBracket@@. As Black's queen controls the e5-square, they does not need to play ...d6 in many lines and, as a result, the f8-bishop can be developed to a more aggresive squares such as b4, c5 or even d6 in some cases. }
6. a3
{ This will be my recommendation against the Taimanov. As I did in Play the Sicilian, Part 1, I am going to try to recommend positions with similar pawn structures. This is the reason why we are going to play the move a3 in quite a number of lines. Being less well-known than the main line, this move -played by string Russian GMs- is the most flexible move by White here and its idea is to pre-empt Black plans with ...a6+b5 and prevent Black's dark-squared bishop to get to b4. }
6... Nf6
{ Probably the most natural move for Black to control the central squares and develop a piece. However, this would already be their first mistake. Let's take advantage of this early development of the knight on f6 to quickly look for ideas with f4+e5 to harass Black @@StartBracket@@the move a3 ideally combines with these pawn advances as it prevents the pins on b4@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Be3
{ This move is a direct transposition to one of the main lines of the Taimanov @@StartBracket@@6.Be3@@EndBracket@@. However, the tournament practice has shown that the move ...Nf6 is an innacurate move order for Black due to the aforementioned pawn pushes. We simply develop another piece that helps to control the center and prepare f4 a bit better. }
7... Be7
{ Delaying ...a6 to aim for a faster development and a quick castling. } 8. f4
{ Following the same plan: playing a quick e5. } 8... Nxd4
{ This move has been tried many times in computer games, but it is a rather unnatural continuation as it helps our queen to develop.   8...d5  9.e5  Nd7  10.h4  . }
9. Qxd4 b6 10. Qd2
{ The simplest. We want to finish our development with Bd3 and push our pawns in a later stage. }
10... Bb7 11. Bd3 a6 12. O-O-O
{ We control the center and we have free hands to attack. Black's king has no safe place to go to. }
*

