17... Nxe3 18. Qxe3 Kh8 { The only attempt to stop Nf6 as much as possible. }
19. Rg4
{ With the idea of playing ...Rh4 to define the game. Here follow some extremely complex lines, but do not worry, we are already winning. }
19... Rd8 20. Rh4 h6 { Black's best attempt to complicate the game. } 21. Nf6
{ With teh idea of playing Qe4 next to decide the game. } 21... Qb7
{ 21...Bb7  22.Ng4  the b7-bishop has stopped Black's little counterplay along the b-file and we are ready now to sac everything on h6. }
22. Qe5 { Defending b2 and centralizing. } 22... Rd4 23. b4
{ This move can be scary to make. However, as we are going to be the first who checkmates, it's not so serious weakening move. }
23... Bd6 { 23...gxf6  24.Rxh6+  Kg8  25.gxf6  . } 24. Qe3
{ We are still attacking d4 to prevent ...cxb4. } 24... e5
{ 24...Qb6  25.Bc2  .   24...Qc7  25.Bc2  clearing the d3-square for the queen. }
25. gxh6 { With an unstoppable attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Taimanov 6.a3 Nf6"]
[Black "6.a3 Nf6 7.Be3 with 8.f4 d6 #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this part of the course we will analyze the ...e6-Sicilians, in which Black keeps the flexibility of their piece development, as we are going to see. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ This is one of the most flexible move orders for Black, as it allows them to choose between the Taimanov Sicilian, the Two Knights Sicilian and it allows playing with ...a6 as well. As this move hits the center directly, it is not easy for White to go for a Maroczy Bind structure directly.   At this point I am going to recommend two moves. The first one -our main line- will be Nc3, which is the standard move. Our idea is to develop our pieces and control the center. However, the party is not over yet. The second move I recommend goes specifically against opponents who have the Taimanov as a main weapon, since we are practically going to make life impossible for them.. }
5. Nc3
{ The knight develops naturally and conyrols some central squares. After this move, our chances of going for a Marozcy structure are gone. However, this will not be a problem.   5.a3!  is the other option and will be analyzed in the Two Knights chapter. }
5... Qc7
{ After this move we are in Taimanov Sicilian territory. This is -in my humble opinion- the best Sicilian for Black after the Najdorf and the Sveshnikov. Black usually plays very flexible by combining pawn pushes on both flanks @@StartBracket@@...a6 and ...b5 or ...h5@@EndBracket@@. As Black's queen controls the e5-square, they does not need to play ...d6 in many lines and, as a result, the f8-bishop can be developed to a more aggresive squares such as b4, c5 or even d6 in some cases. }
6. a3
{ This will be my recommendation against the Taimanov. As I did in Play the Sicilian, Part 1, I am going to try to recommend positions with similar pawn structures. This is the reason why we are going to play the move a3 in quite a number of lines. Being less well-known than the main line, this move -played by string Russian GMs- is the most flexible move by White here and its idea is to pre-empt Black plans with ...a6+b5 and prevent Black's dark-squared bishop to get to b4. }
6... Nf6
{ Probably the most natural move for Black to control the central squares and develop a piece. However, this would already be their first mistake. Let's take advantage of this early development of the knight on f6 to quickly look for ideas with f4+e5 to harass Black @@StartBracket@@the move a3 ideally combines with these pawn advances as it prevents the pins on b4@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Be3
{ This move is a direct transposition to one of the main lines of the Taimanov @@StartBracket@@6.Be3@@EndBracket@@. However, the tournament practice has shown that the move ...Nf6 is an innacurate move order for Black due to the aforementioned pawn pushes. We simply develop another piece that helps to control the center and prepare f4 a bit better. }
7... a6
{ The most played move in practice. Black prevents all the annoying jumps to b5 and, at the same time, prepares the ...b5-push. }
8. f4
{ Controlling directly the center and starting to create some very annoying threats -after e5, the f6-knight has no good squares-. We take advantage of the fact that Black is not completely ready to break in the center with ...d5 to force our opponent to play d6 since, after this, they will adopt a more passive position. }
8... d6 9. Qf3
{ Continuing our piece development, exerting indirect pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal. It is important to develop our queen to f3 because this will allow us to castle long very soon and, besides, we keep on having the g4-square under control for an eventual advance of our g-pawn. }
9... Be7
{ The most natural move, preparing to castle short.   After  9...b5  10.Nxc6!  we take at this point to force Black to recapture with the queen -it would be more annoying to deal with a pin of the e4-pawn on our queen in case Black is able to bring the bishop to the a8-h1 diagonal.  10...Qxc6  11.O-O-O  . }
10. O-O-O
{ A critical moment for Black, who has to decide whether to castle kingside and face our pawn storm or create counterplay on the queenside. }
10... O-O 11. Nxc6 { This is the quickest way to start pushing our kingside. }
11... bxc6
{ 11...Qxc6?!  12.g4  continuing our typical plan. Black takes much longer to carry out the attack because the b-file would be closed. }
12. g4
{ Starting our pawn storm. In this line we have to combine some aggressive moves with prophylactic plans to prevent our opponent's attack. }
12... d5 { Fighting for the center and activating the e7-bishop. } 13. g5
{ The knight has to be kicked away as soon as possible to continue our attack. }
13... dxe4 { The most logical move, getting the d5-square for the knight. } 14.
Nxe4 Nd5
{ If  14...Nxe4  15.Qxe4  we have a better pawn structure, more space, and better coordinated pieces, so we can choose between going for a solid plan that involves the queen exchange on e5 pwith a better endgame or continue attacking with Bd3 and h4 ideas. }
15. Bd3
{ Activating the last piece eyeing at the weakest square of Black's camp. Now the game will become a very interesting fight. There is no need to remember all the lines; it is enough to understand White's attacking ideas. }
15... Rb8 { Looking for some counterplay using the b-file. } 16. Rhg1
{ Tragedy begins to chew on Black's position. Nf6 starts to be a move to seriously consider or slower ideas like Rg3 are in the air, too. }
16... c5 17. c4
{ Stopping Black's c-pawn and kicking the knight away, which was controlling f6. }
17... Nxe3 18. Qxe3 Kh8 { The only attempt to stop Nf6 as much as possible. }
19. Rg4
{ With the idea of playing ...Rh4 to define the game. Here follow some extremely complex lines, but do not worry, we are already winning. }
19... Rd8 20. Rh4 h6 { Black's best attempt to complicate the game. } 21. Nf6
{ With teh idea of playing Qe4 next to decide the game. } 21... Qb7
{ 21...Bb7  22.Ng4  the b7-bishop has stopped Black's little counterplay along the b-file and we are ready now to sac everything on h6. }
22. Qe5 { Defending b2 and centralizing. } 22... Bd6 23. Bc2
{ Pinning the d6-bishop and achieving the perfect coordination of all our pieces. }
23... Qc6 { 23...Qc7  . } 24. Rxh6+ gxh6 25. Nh5+ Bxe5 26. Rxd8+
{ I needed to include this finish. :@@EndBracket@@ } *

