[White "1) Taimanov 6.a3 Nf6"]
[Black "6.a3 Be7 7.Be3 with 8.g4 b5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this part of the course we will analyze the ...e6-Sicilians, in which Black keeps the flexibility of their piece development, as we are going to see. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ This is one of the most flexible move orders for Black, as it allows them to choose between the Taimanov Sicilian, the Two Knights Sicilian and it allows playing with ...a6 as well. As this move hits the center directly, it is not easy for White to go for a Maroczy Bind structure directly.   At this point I am going to recommend two moves. The first one -our main line- will be Nc3, which is the standard move. Our idea is to develop our pieces and control the center. However, the party is not over yet. The second move I recommend goes specifically against opponents who have the Taimanov as a main weapon, since we are practically going to make life impossible for them.. }
5. Nc3
{ The knight develops naturally and conyrols some central squares. After this move, our chances of going for a Marozcy structure are gone. However, this will not be a problem.   5.a3!  is the other option and will be analyzed in the Two Knights chapter. }
5... Qc7
{ After this move we are in Taimanov Sicilian territory. This is -in my humble opinion- the best Sicilian for Black after the Najdorf and the Sveshnikov. Black usually plays very flexible by combining pawn pushes on both flanks @@StartBracket@@...a6 and ...b5 or ...h5@@EndBracket@@. As Black's queen controls the e5-square, they does not need to play ...d6 in many lines and, as a result, the f8-bishop can be developed to a more aggresive squares such as b4, c5 or even d6 in some cases. }
6. a3
{ This will be my recommendation against the Taimanov. As I did in Play the Sicilian, Part 1, I am going to try to recommend positions with similar pawn structures. This is the reason why we are going to play the move a3 in quite a number of lines. Being less well-known than the main line, this move -played by string Russian GMs- is the most flexible move by White here and its idea is to pre-empt Black plans with ...a6+b5 and prevent Black's dark-squared bishop to get to b4. }
6... Be7
{ In this order Black tries to delay momentarily the development of the g8-knight in order to be able to act in a more flexible way in the face of pawn advances on the kingside. }
7. Be3
{ Continuing our standard development, keeping all our options still open. }
7... a6
{ Continuing to play ambiguously is quite interesting, as Black prepares the typical queenside expansion. Several Taimanov experts have played this line as Black, especially Indian players -including our Chessable friend Harikrishna. }
8. g4
{ Gaining some space quicly on the kingside, taking advantage of the fact that Black is now ready to react in the center with ...d5. This move also prevents the development of the knight on g8, as our idea is to bring our pawn to g5. }
8... b5
{ Black ignores our g-pawn advance and keeps on creating counterplay on the queenside.   8...Nf6  9.g5  Ng8  10.h4  . }
9. Nxc6
{ This move is usually stronger after Black plays ...b5. In general, the best ways to take on c6 are either with the b-pawn -in order to achieve the ...d5 break to open the b-file- or with the bishop, with the idea to exert some pressure along the diagonal and clear the b-file or push ...a5+...b4. Having played ...b5, Black cannot get back to these two ideas anymore. }
9... dxc6 10. Qf3
{ Continuing with our typical development. The queen defends h1 to be able to play an eventual g5 in case Black plays ...h6 -otherwise, after h4 the rook would be hanging after hxg5- and now we are ready to castle long. }
10... Bb7 11. O-O-O
{ We keep developing our pieces. We want to play g5 to control the g8-knight possible squares.   11.g5?!  Rd8  . }
11... c5
{ 11...h6  As in other lines, Black does not solve anything, it only creates a hook that will allow us to open the h-file.  12.h4  insisting on g5. }
12. Bf4 Qc6
{ Reaching what could be the most critical position of the whole line. Either g5 and Bg2 are extremely concrete -and very interesting- lines; however, after an extensive analysis, it seems that Black is very close to equalizing in both of them.   12...e5?  13.Be3  and the light squares are so weak. }
13. Qe3 { We are ready for Nd5. } 13... b4 14. Nd5 exd5 15. exd5 Qb6
{ If  15...Qa4  16.Bc4!!  finishing our development with a winning advantage. Once a rook comes to e1, Black's king will not survive. }
16. axb4 Qxb4 17. Bg2 { Black's king cannot move. } *

