9... dxc6 10. Qf3
{ Continuing with our typical development. The queen defends h1 to be able to play an eventual g5 in case Black plays ...h6 -otherwise, after h4 the rook would be hanging after hxg5- and now we are ready to castle long. }
10... Bb7 11. O-O-O
{ We keep developing our pieces. We want to play g5 to control the g8-knight possible squares.   11.g5?!  Rd8  . }
11... c5
{ 11...h6  As in other lines, Black does not solve anything, it only creates a hook that will allow us to open the h-file.  12.h4  insisting on g5. }
12. Bf4 Qc6
{ Reaching what could be the most critical position of the whole line. Either g5 and Bg2 are extremely concrete -and very interesting- lines; however, after an extensive analysis, it seems that Black is very close to equalizing in both of them.   12...e5?  13.Be3  and the light squares are so weak. }
13. Qe3 { We are ready for Nd5. } 13... Rd8
{ Black hopes to release the tension on the d-file before developing the knight. We should be more careful with a ...b4 push by Black, as nowit will not be possible to play Nd5. }
14. Bg2 { Renewing the Nd5 idea. } 14... Nf6
{ 14...b4?  15.Nd5  exd5  16.exd5  and, again, our h-rook gets closer to the center and could exert an annoying pressure from there. }
15. Rxd8+ Bxd8 16. Rd1
{ We keep on exerting pressure along the d-file to prevent Black from castling short. }
16... O-O { 16...Nxg4?  17.Qg3  . } 17. g5 Nd7 18. Qd3
{ Keeping the possibility to swing the queen across the 3rd rank. } 18... Bc8
{ 18...Nb6  19.Qxd8  . } 19. Bd6 Bxg5+
{ We have sacrificed a pawn in exchange of some counterplay along the g-file.   19...Re8  20.f4  with a nice space advantage. Black's pieces are crowded together, barely able to move. }
20. Kb1 Rd8
{ 20...Re8  21.Qg3  all our pieces to the party! Black can barely move. } 21.
Qg3 Bh6 22. e5 { Our piece activity decides the game. } *

