[White "2) Taimanov 6.a3 a6"]
[Black "6.a3 a6 7.Nxc6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this part of the course we will analyze the ...e6-Sicilians, in which Black keeps the flexibility of their piece development, as we are going to see. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ This is one of the most flexible move orders for Black, as it allows them to choose between the Taimanov Sicilian, the Two Knights Sicilian and it allows playing with ...a6 as well. As this move hits the center directly, it is not easy for White to go for a Maroczy Bind structure directly.   At this point I am going to recommend two moves. The first one -our main line- will be Nc3, which is the standard move. Our idea is to develop our pieces and control the center. However, the party is not over yet. The second move I recommend goes specifically against opponents who have the Taimanov as a main weapon, since we are practically going to make life impossible for them.. }
5. Nc3
{ The knight develops naturally and conyrols some central squares. After this move, our chances of going for a Marozcy structure are gone. However, this will not be a problem.   5.a3!  is the other option and will be analyzed in the Two Knights chapter. }
5... Qc7
{ After this move we are in Taimanov Sicilian territory. This is -in my humble opinion- the best Sicilian for Black after the Najdorf and the Sveshnikov. Black usually plays very flexible by combining pawn pushes on both flanks @@StartBracket@@...a6 and ...b5 or ...h5@@EndBracket@@. As Black's queen controls the e5-square, they does not need to play ...d6 in many lines and, as a result, the f8-bishop can be developed to a more aggresive squares such as b4, c5 or even d6 in some cases. }
6. a3
{ This will be my recommendation against the Taimanov. As I did in Play the Sicilian, Part 1, I am going to try to recommend positions with similar pawn structures. This is the reason why we are going to play the move a3 in quite a number of lines. Being less well-known than the main line, this move -played by strong Russian GMs- is the most flexible move by White here and its idea is to pre-empt Black plans with ...a6+...b5 and prevent their dark-squared bishop to get to b4. }
6... a6
{ The best move order for Black, as this is the most flexible move together with ...Be7. Black prepares ...b5 and prevents all of our knights' jumps once and for all. }
7. Nxc6
{ The key idea of this line. It has rarely been tested compared to the main lines. Despite this, top GMs like Karjakin have already played it.   The point of playing Nxc6 so quickly is to gather the most amount of information possible regarding Black's plan in the shortest possible time, since depending on which piece recaptures on c6 we will decide how to set up the rest of our pieces. }
7... Qxc6
{ The most aggressive capture of all the possible ones, which tries to keep the maximum Taimanov flavor possible. The fact that this move is so natural, besides the fact that I like White's position so much is one of the reasons why I decided to recommend this line.    The queen does not control the e5-square anymore, and this means that ...Nf6 is not going to be easy to play because Black will have to deal with White's e5-push. }
8. h4
{ The trendy move! The idea is to gain space with h5 to attack Black's king after an eventual short castling. Besides, we enable the rook to go to h3 and all that is made kepping the flexibility of all of our pieces. }
8... Nf6 9. Qf3
{ In this case, we develop our queen to f3 to leave room for the light-square bishop to go to d3if necessary. Besides, from f3 the queen controls the f4-square to be able to play Bf4 against BLack's Qc7. Our next move will be h5 to fix some weaknesses. }
9... b5 10. h5 Bb7 11. Bd3 h6 12. Qg3 { Reaching our ideal setup. } *

