{ This will be my recommendation against the Taimanov. As I did in Play the Sicilian, Part 1, I am going to try to recommend positions with similar pawn structures. This is the reason why we are going to play the move a3 in quite a number of lines. Being less well-known than the main line, this move -played by strong Russian GMs- is the most flexible move by White here and its idea is to pre-empt Black plans with ...a6+...b5 and prevent their dark-squared bishop to get to b4. }
