{ After this move comes a mass simplification that leaves black in a rather inferior endgame. According to the engines, the position is equal, but in practice I consider extremely difficult for Black to hold the position. }
15. Bxf4 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Bxf4 17. gxf4 dxe4 18. Bxe4 O-O-O
{ Sacrificing a pawn, after which we will have a 3 vs 1 majority on the queenside.   18...Rc8  19.Rh5  . }
19. Bxc6 Rd4
{ Black needs to activate the pieces quickly to compensate that they are material down. }
20. Bf3 Rxf4 21. O-O-O Bg4
{ This is the line in which Black equalizes according to the modern engines.   21...Kc7  22.Rd3  . }
22. Rh4 h5 23. Bxg4+ Rxg4 24. Rxg4 hxg4 25. Rf1
{ Maybe with extremely precise engine moves Black can keep the balance in this endgame. However, in a practical game, this 3 vs 1 is going to be a nightmare for Black to hold. }
*

