14. Bf4 { Developing with tempo and forcing the rook to a worse square. } 14...
Ra8 15. b5 dxe4 { 15...cxb5  16.Nxb5  . } 16. fxe4
{ From here, the pawn further restricts Black's pieces and, above all, the capture on b5 becomes much less desirable as we will recapture with the knight. }
16... Bb7
{ Very risky move. Black gets ready to take on b5 in better conditions, but they allow us to bring a pawn to b6 that can be defended.   If  16...cxb5  17.Nxb5  Kf8  18.Rb1  White has a lot of piece activity to compensate our worse structure. }
17. b6
{ If we manage to bring the knight to a4 we will have a great advantage. Black should prevent this by bringing their pawn to a4. }
17... a4 18. Nb1 Nd7
{ 18...Bc5  19.Nd2  Ke7  20.Nc4  .   19...Bxb6  20.Rb1  . } 19. Nd2 e5 20. Be3
{ Finally we have managed to defend the pawn, which gives us a lot of space and headaches for Black. Despite this, I consider this a high risk position for both sides and, therefore, I have recommended an alternative line. }
