{ For the moment we are not worried about the capture on d3 since after Rxd3 we still have very annoying plans regarding the control of the black squares with moves like Na4. }
14... h6
{ A natural move, with the idea of castling on the kingside.   After  14...a5  Black is really threatening to take on d3 now as we are not in time to go for the Na4 plan.  15.Be2  h6  16.g4  .   15...dxe4  16.Rh5  a recurrent theme when the knight is on c5.   14...O-O??  15.Bxc5  Bxc5  16.exd5  . }
15. Be2 O-O
{ If  15...dxe4  16.Rh5!!  once again, this move is very strong.  16...Nd7  17.Nxe4  .   16...f5  17.fxe4  . }
16. g4 a5 17. f4
{ Just in time. The idea is to keep the bishops on the board by playing Bf3 in case Black goes ...Ba6. Besides, we gain some space on the kingside. I feel it is very easy to reach this position, as Black's moves are very natural and we can get here by differente move orders. }
17... Nxe4 { 17...Ba6  18.Bf3  . } 18. Nxe4 dxe4 19. g5
{ In return for the sacrificed pawn we have a 3vs2 pawn majority on the queenside and, in addition, some chances to attack, a better poawn structure, and the chance to get the pawn back in a short while. }
19... hxg5 20. fxg5 Rd8
{ Black needs to trade a pair of rooks to release the pressure on the h-file.   20...Ba6  21.Bxa6  Rxa6  22.Rh3  . }
21. Rxd8+ Bxd8 22. Rd1 Be7
{ 22...Bc7  23.a4  the fact that our pieces are active and that Black has a lot of weaknesses not only compesate the pawn, but also gives us a very nice position. }
23. g6
{ This pawn sac is a recurrent theme in this kind of endgame. Black's extra pawns, as they are doubled and isolated, are practically non-existent and, besides, Black's pawn structure is becoming worse and worse. }
23... fxg6 24. Rd4
{ Black's position is full of weaknesses, which are going to fall one by one. }
