6... a6
{ The best move order for Black, as this is the most flexible move together with ...Be7. Black prepares ...b5 and prevents all of our knights' jumps once and for all. }
7. Nxc6
{ The key idea of this line. It has rarely been tested compared to the main lines. Despite this, top GMs like Karjakin have already played it.   The point of playing Nxc6 so quickly is to gather the most amount of information possible regarding Black's plan in the shortest possible time, since depending on which piece recaptures on c6 we will decide how to set up the rest of our pieces. }
7... dxc6
{ The most solid capture of the 3 possible, after which we reach a position with an almost symmetrical structure. The main key to our advantage in this position lies in the weaknesses on Black's dark squares on the queenside and our development advantage.   Our plans include the simple piece development with O-O, a possible f4 breaking the center in case Black goes ...e5 or even the massive space gain on the queenside by means of pawn pushes. }
8. Bd3
{ The most flexible move, developing the bishop to its most natural square, from where it points directly to a future castle from Black and overdefends e4 just in case. }
8... e5
{ Black gives one more development tempo away in exchange for fighting quickly for the center. }
9. O-O
{ We continue making our lives easier with this natural development move. Black has only developed the queen so far and we have already castled and we are ready for a possible f4 -the point for this push to work is be sure that, after exf4 and Bxf4, it is not possible for Black to play...Bd6 conveniently. }
9... Be6
{ The best move order for Black. However, from my point of view, it is extremely difficult to get to this conlusion over the board. Black blocks the e-file and, at the same time, develops their bishop controlling important squares such as c4 and f7. The real point is that after f4 Black can capture and continue with ...Bd6 after Axf4 without being worried about e5. }
10. Qe2
{ Improving our queen and getting ready for f4.   The direct  10.f4?  does not work:  10...exf4  11.Bxf4  Bd6  the point of 10.Qe2 is to be able to play e5! in this position  12.e5?  does not work here due to  12...Bxe5  . }
10... Nf6 { This move does nothing to stop our threat. } 11. f4 Bc5+
{ 11...exf4  12.Bxf4  . } 12. Kh1 exf4 { 12...h6  13.f5  . } 13. Bxf4 Qe7 14.
Bg5 h6 15. Bh4 g5 { 15...Bg4  16.Qd2  g5  17.e5  . } 16. e5 Nd5
{ 16...Nd7  17.Bg3  . } 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Bg3
{ We will follow with Rf6+Raf1 with good control of the position. } *

