1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. a3
{ When I discovered this move, I could not resist recommending it. It is designed specifically against Taimanov players @@StartBracket@@the best continuation here is ...Nf6 and, after Nc3, we will transpose directly to the Two Knights with a3@@@EndBracket@@. However, most Taimanov players will have no idea of that position and will try to transpose to what they know with ...Qc7, after which they will get a nasty surprise. }
5... d5
{ It makes sense for Black to try to open the position because the move a3 does not immediately fight for the center. However, it is not entirely true because the move a3 controls b4 and, therefore, Nc3 will be stronger. }
6. exd5 Qxd5 7. Be3
{ We will play Nc3 next and, as the pin on b4 is not possible anymore, Black loses a lot of tempi. }
7... Nf6 8. Nc3 Qe5
{ 8...Qa5?!  thanks to the fact that our pawn is on a3, this move does not create concrete threats and, besides,we can attack Black's queen with Nb3 at some point.  9.Qf3  Bd7  10.Nb3  keeping on developing comfortably, with a nice edge. }
9. Nxc6
{ Going for this concrete move to take advantage of the fact that we are up in development. }
9... bxc6 10. Qd4
{ 10.Qf3!?  is also good, but it complicates the position a bit too much unnecessarily. }
10... Qxd4 11. Bxd4
{ With a comfortable endgame thanks to the fact that our structure is better than our opponent's. }
