1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. a3
{ When I discovered this move, I could not resist recommending it. It is designed specifically against Taimanov players @@StartBracket@@the best continuation here is ...Nf6 and, after Nc3, we will transpose directly to the Two Knights with a3@@@EndBracket@@. However, most Taimanov players will have no idea of that position and will try to transpose to what they know with ...Qc7, after which they will get a nasty surprise. }
5... Bc5
{ This is one of the best moves for Black here. However, I find it difficult to play if we don't know it because Black's setup is far away from the familiar ones. }
6. Nb3 { Winning a tempo and continuing our development. } 6... Bb6 7. Nc3 Nf6
{ I have the feeling that this will become one of the main lines for Black, so I leave you with two options: a more quiet one and a quite crazy one as well. }
8. Bg5
{ Pinning the knight and preparing f4. Black should play very precise now. }
8... O-O 9. f4 { White's coordination is perfect. } 9... d6 10. Qd3
{ O-O-O is coming. All of our pieces are amazingly coordinated. } *

