[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. a3
{ When I discovered this move, I could not resist recommending it. It is designed specifically against Taimanov players @@StartBracket@@the best continuation here is ...Nf6 and, after Nc3, we will transpose directly to the Two Knights with a3@@@EndBracket@@. However, most Taimanov players will have no idea of that position and will try to transpose to what they know with ...Qc7, after which they will get a nasty surprise. }
5... Bc5
{ This is one of the best moves for Black here. However, I find it difficult to play if we don't know it because Black's setup is far away from the familiar ones. }
6. Nb3 { Winning a tempo and continuing our development. } 6... Bb6 7. Nc3 Nf6
{ I have the feeling that this will become one of the main lines for Black, so I leave you with two options: a more quiet one and a quite crazy one as well. }
8. Bg5
{ Pinning the knight and preparing f4. Black should play very precise now. }
8... h6 9. Bh4 d5
{ This central break is key for Black before f4 comes.   9...O-O  10.f4  and, again, this push is incredibly strong and very easy to underestimate by our opponents. }
10. Bb5 { Continuing our development. The move e5 is another possible threat. }
10... d4 11. Na4 e5
{ It is important for Black to seize the center.   11...O-O  Black should not allow f4  12.Nxb6  axb6  13.f4  this pawn push allows us to seize the center and we are threatening e5 as well. }
12. Qe2
{ THe key is to defend the b5-bishop to be able to take on b6 without ...Qxb6 being possible due to the fact that we will double our opponent's pawns on the f-file. }
12... O-O
{ 12...Qd6  13.Nxb6  axb6  14.O-O  with a better position thanks to the bishop pair and Black's weak doubled pawns on the queenside. }
13. Nxb6 axb6 14. h3
{ A very useful and quite flexible move, preventing ...Bg4 and giving the h2-square for the bishop or the king. WE want to provoke BLack to play ...g5, which would create additional weaknesses. }
14... Be6 15. Nd2
{ Relocating the knight now that it will be more difficult to defend the e5-pawn. }
15... Rc8
{ 15...g5  16.Bg3  with the idea of breaking the position open with an eventual c3 and highlighting BLack's problems with the e5-square. }
16. Rc1
{ Preparing an eventual c3 @@StartBracket@@especially after g5@@EndBracket@@ and defending c2. }
