1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. a3
{ When I discovered this move, I could not resist recommending it. It is designed specifically against Taimanov players @@StartBracket@@the best continuation here is ...Nf6 and, after Nc3, we will transpose directly to the Two Knights with a3@@@EndBracket@@. However, most Taimanov players will have no idea of that position and will try to transpose to what they know with ...Qc7, after which they will get a nasty surprise. }
5... Qc7
{ If our opponent plays the Taimanov, I am almost sure that we will see this position on the board. }
6. Be3
{ This move is the key of this variation. In case of  6...a6  we will go into a Maroczy structure and in case of  6...Nf6  we will directly go into a line that is not considered particularly good against the Taimanov. }
6... a6 7. c4
{ The key move. Keeping the flexibility with the development of the b1-knight gives us this extra possibility, which will be very annoying for our opponents. }
