1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. a3
{ When I discovered this move, I could not resist recommending it. It is designed specifically against Taimanov players @@StartBracket@@the best continuation here is ...Nf6 and, after Nc3, we will transpose directly to the Two Knights with a3@@@EndBracket@@. However, most Taimanov players will have no idea of that position and will try to transpose to what they know with ...Qc7, after which they will get a nasty surprise. }
5... a6 6. Be3
{ Keeping in hand the possibility of going into a Maroczy Bind. } 6... Nf6 7.
Nc3 Be7
{ 7...d6  transposes to the next chapter.   7...Qc7  8.f4  transposes to the first one. }
8. f4
{ We want to force Black to go ...d6 to be able to develop our queen to f3 without being in the way. }
8... d6 9. Qf3 e5
{ The only -and the best- move that does not transpose to the other lines that we have already seen via the other move order. }
10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. h3
{ Preventing both ...Bg4 and ...Ng4 and we can give rise to O-O-O. } 11... Rb8
{ 11...O-O  12.O-O-O  Qc7  13.g4  with good counterplay.   After  11...exf4  12.Bxf4  the d6-pawn suffers after O-O-O. }
12. fxe5
{ As the a1-h8 diagonal will become weak after b3, it is important to take on e5 first to ensure it is closed in the future. }
12... dxe5 13. b3
{ After this we get into a curious position. Our pieces are in good -and active- squares while Black's struggle to find a place to go. Our idea is to go Na4 to control even more squares and so being able to transfer this knight to a better place. }
13... O-O 14. Na4 { Preventing ...Qa5 ideas and intending to go Be2. } 14...
Be6 15. Be2 *

