[White "3) Anti-Taimanov Move Order"]
[Black "5...e5 6.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. a3
{ When I discovered this move, I could not resist recommending it. It is designed specifically against Taimanov players @@StartBracket@@the best continuation here is ...Nf6 and, after Nc3, we will transpose directly to the Two Knights with a3@@@EndBracket@@. However, most Taimanov players will have no idea of that position and will try to transpose to what they know with ...Qc7, after which they will get a nasty surprise. }
5... e5
{ This was Gukesh's attempt against this line against Nico in the olympiad @@StartBracket@@I was coaching the Swiss team@@EndBracket@@. We had just prepared a3 as White for this game.   Nico continued Nb5 which, although it gives White a certain plus, sin practice it is not so easy, as the pawn on a3 not only is not useful in this line but it can become an issue because it takes the a3 square away from the knight, which could go there in some lines. }
6. Nf3
{ The simplest move, taking advantage of the fact that the a3-pawn controls b4 to help our comfortable -and standard- development. We will reach a Najdorf type of structure in which the knight is typically misplaced on c6. Besides -and especially now-, the Bg5+Bxf6 plan will be stronger because Black will not be able to take with the knight and the light squares will become extremely weak. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 d6 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Bc4
{ Reaching a very comfortable position to play. White will continue with moves such as Nd5, Qd3 and O-O. }
*

