1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. a3
{ When I discovered this move, I could not resist recommending it. It is designed specifically against Taimanov players @@StartBracket@@the best continuation here is ...Nf6 and, after Nc3, we will transpose directly to the Two Knights with a3@@@EndBracket@@. However, most Taimanov players will have no idea of that position and will try to transpose to what they know with ...Qc7, after which they will get a nasty surprise. }
5... Nf6
{ The most concrete move, after which we will directly transpose to the standard lines after Nc3. }
6. Nc3 d6
{ It makes much sense to control the e5-square directly, but this loses the possibility of playing ...d5 in one move. Let's take advantage of it. }
7. Be3 Be7 8. h3
{ This is my recommendation, and a way of playing that can be seen in other Sicilian move orders. However, this move has been played in only two amateur games. Logically, we want to play g4 and we also keep the flexibility with our king, which we could bring either to the kingside or to the queenside.   8.g4?!  is premature due to  8...Nxd4!  9.Qxd4  e5  10.Qa4+  Bd7  11.Bb5  Nxg4  . }
8... e5 9. Nb3
{ Now we want to go for a quick g4, so Black has to prepare the ...d5-break.   9.Nf3!?  is a good version of a line that Nakamura played in the Candidates. }
9... Be6
{ 9...O-O  10.g4  and g5+h4 comes next, highly cramping Black's pieces. } 10.
Qd3 { Preparing Nd5 and O-O-O. } 10... d5
{ Black wants to trade pieces massively to get into the endgame. } 11. exd5
Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Bxd5
{ It makes no sense to take with the bishop.   12...Qxd5!  13.Nc5  and White gains the bishop pair and has a nice endgame ahead. }
13. O-O-O Be6 14. Qc3
{ Nc5 is next, getting the bishop pair with a huge initiative. } *

