[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. a3
{ When I discovered this move, I could not resist recommending it. It is designed specifically against Taimanov players @@StartBracket@@the best continuation here is ...Nf6 and, after Nc3, we will transpose directly to the Two Knights with a3@@@EndBracket@@. However, most Taimanov players will have no idea of that position and will try to transpose to what they know with ...Qc7, after which they will get a nasty surprise. }
5... Nf6
{ The most concrete move, after which we will directly transpose to the standard lines after Nc3. }
6. Nc3 d6
{ It makes much sense to control the e5-square directly, but this loses the possibility of playing ...d5 in one move. Let's take advantage of it. }
7. Be3 Be7 8. h3
{ This is my recommendation, and a way of playing that can be seen in other Sicilian move orders. However, this move has been played in only two amateur games. Logically, we want to play g4 and we also keep the flexibility with our king, which we could bring either to the kingside or to the queenside.   8.g4?!  is premature due to  8...Nxd4!  9.Qxd4  e5  10.Qa4+  Bd7  11.Bb5  Nxg4  . }
8... O-O 9. g4 { Following our logical idea. } 9... Nd7
{ Black's best attempt, for sure, is this prophylactic move against g5. Things will get complicated. }
10. Be2 { A useful move to control squares like f3 against jumps such as Ne5. }
10... Nc5
{ 10...a6  11.h4  another usual move, taking advantage of the fact that Black is almost forced to go ...Nxd4 to continue the development.  11...Qc7  12.h5  continuing our advance, while Black has not done it yet.   11...Nxd4  12.Qxd4  g5 and 0-0-0 are next with a clear advantage, as our attack is quicker.   10...Nde5  11.Qd2!  Na5  12.b3  Preventing the only source of Black's counterplay and continuing our expansion with a clear advantage.   If  11...Bd7  12.O-O-O  . }
11. Nxc6
{ The most quiet option, reaching by force a better endgame thanks to Black's bad structure. }
11... bxc6 12. Bxc5 dxc5 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Rd1 Rd4
{ 14...Bb7  15.h4  and g5 comes next to limit the bishop's activity. } 15. b3
{ Black is close to equalize with precise play. However, in practice this position seems very annoying to me; we will go Bc4 and take advantage of Black's long-term weaknesses. }
