[White "4) Two Knights Main Line"]
[Black "5...Nf6 6.Nc3 with 7.Nxc6 #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. a3
{ When I discovered this move, I could not resist recommending it. It is designed specifically against Taimanov players @@StartBracket@@the best continuation here is ...Nf6 and, after Nc3, we will transpose directly to the Two Knights with a3@@@EndBracket@@. However, most Taimanov players will have no idea of that position and will try to transpose to what they know with ...Qc7, after which they will get a nasty surprise. }
5... Nf6
{ The most concrete move, after which we will directly transpose to the standard lines after Nc3. }
6. Nc3 Be7
{ Playing this move is not as easy if our opponents do not know it beforehand, as it allows Nxc6+e5. Therefore, I think we will face d6 more often over the board. }
7. Nxc6
{ 7.Be3  is also a possible and interesting option, but we cannot go for the h3 idea because Black can play ...d5 in one move. }
7... bxc6 8. e5 Nd5 9. Qg4
{ With the idea of either creating weaknesses quickly or force Black to lose the right to castle. At the same time, we develop our pieces with tempo. }
9... g6 10. Bd2
{ This is my recommendation. This move deviates from the most played ones, but our point is just developing the bishop with the idea of taking on c3 with this piece and prepare to go O-O-O. }
10... Rb8 { We are following the game Anand-Saric. } 11. Na4
{ Defending b2 and preparing c4 to kick the knight away.   11.Bd3!?  Anand decided to sacrifice the b2-pawn -which was not taken in the game- and, after a complicated game, a draw was agreed. ½-½  @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2753@@EndBracket@@-Saric,I @@StartBracket@@2653@@EndBracket@@ Zagreb 2021 }
11... O-O
{ 11...f5  12.Qg3  the ...f5 push has created irreversible weaknesses. Now it will be more difficult to go ...d6 due to the fact that this move would create permanent weaknesses on e5 and e6. }
12. Be2
{ Developing and keeping the king flexible regarding where is it going to go. }
12... d6 13. c4 { Get out of there! } 13... Nb6 14. exd6 Bxd6 15. Nxb6
{ 15.Nc3  taking advantage of the fact that White's knight is off the game to bring ours to the center. WE have a better structure and, in addition, Black's king is very weak. }
15... Qxb6 16. Bc3
{ With a comfortable position thanks to our strong bishop on c3. } *

