[White "5) 4...Nc6 & 5...a6"]
[Black "4...Nc6 & 5...a6 with 6.Bf4 and 7.e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 a6
{ One of the fashionable Sicilians, recently played by Rapport in the Candidates Tournament as well as by Andreikin and Nepo on numerous occasions. }
6. Bf4
{ White controls some key squares as Black's queen is not on c7 yet. Now e5 will always be an option after ...Nf6.   6.a3!?  it seems difficult for Black to avoid transposing to the other lines we have studied in this course after this move. However, I think it is good to know another extra option. }
6... Nf6 { This move does not prevent our idea. } 7. e5
{ The knight does not have a decent retreat. } 7... Qc7
{ Taking advantage of the pin with a developing move.   7...Ng8  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.Ne4  with a huge advantage in development.   7...Nd5  8.Nxd5  exd5  9.Qd2  going for O-O-O next with a much better structure and Black has a weakness on d5. }
8. Nxc6
{ Removing the defender of the e5-square and at the same time we force to take with the pawn. }
8... dxc6
{ If  8...bxc6  9.Bg3!  Nd5  10.Ne4  swe continue our development amd prepare the move c4 once we are castled. }
9. Bg3
{ Leaving the bishop on a defended square and moving it away from a possible attack after ...Cd5. }
9... Nd7 { 9...Nd5  10.Ne4  intending to go O-O and c4 comes next. } 10. Bd3 b5
{ 11...Nxe5?!  11.O-O  and Black cannot adequately defend their pieces. } 11.
Qe2
{ The e5-pawn is an amazing wedge. White will continue with O-O and f4 and we also want to bring our knight to e4. }
*

