1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 a6
{ One of the fashionable Sicilians, recently played by Rapport in the Candidates Tournament as well as by Andreikin and Nepo on numerous occasions. }
6. Bf4
{ White controls some key squares as Black's queen is not on c7 yet. Now e5 will always be an option after ...Nf6.   6.a3!?  it seems difficult for Black to avoid transposing to the other lines we have studied in this course after this move. However, I think it is good to know another extra option. }
6... Qf6
{ The 2nd most played move in this position. This move is based on a trick that Black seems to have at their disposal after we play Be3; however, it will not work, as we will see later on.   Si  6...Qb6  7.Nb3  Bb4  8.Qg4  Black's development is not very harmonious, to put it mildly.   7...Nf6  8.a3  transposing to the Grivas variation, already studied in Part 1  (@@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/play-the-open-sicilian-part-1/course/97623/@@LinkEnd@@)  of this 2-part course. }
7. Be3 { The queen does nothing on f6. } 7... Bc5
{ This would be the only way of justifying Black's development. However,...   7...Bb4  8.Qd3  . }
8. Nxe6 Bxe3 { 8...dxe6  9.Bxc5  . } 9. Nc7+ Kd8 10. fxe3
{ We are a pawn up and Black's king is on a very awful position. Besides, the c7-knight is taboo due to the other knight's fork on d5. }
*

