[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 a6
{ One of the fashionable Sicilians, recently played by Rapport in the Candidates Tournament as well as by Andreikin and Nepo on numerous occasions. }
6. Bf4
{ White controls some key squares as Black's queen is not on c7 yet. Now e5 will always be an option after ...Nf6.   6.a3!?  it seems difficult for Black to avoid transposing to the other lines we have studied in this course after this move. However, I think it is good to know another extra option. }
6... d6
{ The main move, controlling e5 to be able to develop the knight to f6 comfortably. }
7. Nxc6
{ Going for this type of structure as neither the pawn on d6 nor the pawn on a6 are particularly useful here. }
7... bxc6 8. h4
{ Winning space and giving the g5-square to the bishop and h3 to the rook. }
8... h5
{ This means that in the long run, when black castles, his king will be much weaker. Besides, the g5-square will be easily used by our bishop. }
9. Qd2 e5 10. Bg5 Nf6
{ If  10...Qc7  11.Bc4  so it does not make sense for Black to lose a tenpo with the queen, as we enjoy a perfect development nad the second player will also truggle to develop their kingside pieces due to the d6-weakness. 0-0-0 comes next. }
11. Bc4
{ Our plan is simple, and with the bishop on b3 there is nothing to worry about. }
