[White "6) Kan"]
[Black "4...a6 5.Bd3 with 6.O-O and 8.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Sicilian, one of the favorites of Grandmasters in Open tournaments to play for a win against inferior opponents thanks to the great unbalance it creates.   I myself have used c4 against this variation on many occasions. However, I consider that the most recent theory has shown that Black has good chances to get quite close to equality by means of concrete lines focused on a fast break on d5. }
5. Bd3
{ In this case we are going to delay a little the development of the b1-knight since we will adopt a Maroczy-type structure in a great number of situations. }
5... Nf6
{ Black takes advantage of the check on a5 to develop without controlling the e5-square momentarily. }
6. O-O { Continuing our development keeping the flexibility. } 6... d6
{ 6...e5  7.Nb3  d6  8.c4  reaching a very favorable pawn structure -basically a hedgehog-like type of structure in which Black would have played ...e5-. We continue with our development with a nice advantage while Black's main issue is the lack of a plausible break since d5 was its main asset and now it will be practically impossible to carry it out.   6...Qc7  . }
7. c4 { Getting the desired structure. } 7... g6
{ A very frequent system to face. We again develop our pieces to the center and this will be enough to get a nice advantage. }
8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Be2
{ As almost always when we have this structure, we continue developing the queen and the rooks to the center next. }
*

