1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Sicilian, one of the favorites of Grandmasters in Open tournaments to play for a win against inferior opponents thanks to the great unbalance it creates.   I myself have used c4 against this variation on many occasions. However, I consider that the most recent theory has shown that Black has good chances to get quite close to equality by means of concrete lines focused on a fast break on d5. }
5. Bd3
{ In this case we are going to delay a little the development of the b1-knight since we will adopt a Maroczy-type structure in a great number of situations. }
5... Nc6 { This is a very favorable version of this structure. } 6. Nxc6 bxc6
7. O-O d5
{ 7...Qc7  8.c4  followed by Nc3 and Be3 finishing our development. We are very comfortable in this Maroczy structure. }
8. c4
{ Encouraging Black to take either of the pawns to create them more pawn islands. }
8... Nf6 9. Qa4 Bd7
{ 9...d4  10.c5  gaining more space, something that Black has not. } 10. e5
{ The knight does not have a good square. } 10... Ng4
{ 10...Ng8  11.Nd2  and Black's development is disastrous. WE will follow Re1 next. }
11. cxd5 Nxe5 12. dxe6 Nxd3 13. exd7+ Qxd7 14. Rd1
{ Reaching a position in which we have a safer king and better development and pawn structure. Now we have to finish our development and put pressure on c6. }
