1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Sicilian, one of the favorites of Grandmasters in Open tournaments to play for a win against inferior opponents thanks to the great unbalance it creates.   I myself have used c4 against this variation on many occasions. However, I consider that the most recent theory has shown that Black has good chances to get quite close to equality by means of concrete lines focused on a fast break on d5. }
5. Bd3
{ In this case we are going to delay a little the development of the b1-knight since we will adopt a Maroczy-type structure in a great number of situations. }
5... Nc6 { This is a very favorable version of this structure. } 6. Nxc6 dxc6
7. Bf4 { Preventing e5 with a development move. } 7... Qf6
{ The most played move, putting pressure on both weak points, but this loses a lot of tempi.   If  7...Nf6  8.O-O  followed by Nd2. If black fails to bring a pawn to e5 the position is quite bad because their pieces do not develop correctly. }
8. Be3 Qxb2
{ After  8...e5  9.Nd2  Black is too far behind in development. We will aim at controlling the b6-square. }
9. Nd2 Nf6 10. O-O
{ We are jumping to c4 with the knight and getting the pawn to a5 to take advantage of the weaknesses on Black's camp as well as their lack in development. }
