1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Sicilian, one of the favorites of Grandmasters in Open tournaments to play for a win against inferior opponents thanks to the great unbalance it creates.   I myself have used c4 against this variation on many occasions. However, I consider that the most recent theory has shown that Black has good chances to get quite close to equality by means of concrete lines focused on a fast break on d5. }
5. Bd3
{ In this case we are going to delay a little the development of the b1-knight since we will adopt a Maroczy-type structure in a great number of situations. }
5... Qc7 { Controlling e5 and keeping the flexibility. } 6. O-O
{ Again keeping all our flexibility intact. } 6... Nc6 7. Nxc6 dxc6 8. f4
{ Gaining some space. WE will bring our queen to the kingside and we will develop the b1-knight to d2 or c3. Against Black's ...e5-push we can play f5 to expand on the kingside or keep the tension exploiting our advantage in development. }
8... e5
{ If  8...Bc5+  9.Kh1  e5  10.Qe1  the queen heads to g3 and we can still go for the aforementioned plans with a4+a5. }
9. Qe1
{ As we almost always go for the square g3 with the queen, it is easy to see that a move like ...e5, opening the position completely, should not be good for Black when their development is practically null. }
9... Nf6 10. a4
{ Intending to fix the b6-weakness with a5 and bring our knight to c4. } *

