1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Sicilian, one of the favorites of Grandmasters in Open tournaments to play for a win against inferior opponents thanks to the great unbalance it creates.   I myself have used c4 against this variation on many occasions. However, I consider that the most recent theory has shown that Black has good chances to get quite close to equality by means of concrete lines focused on a fast break on d5. }
5. Bd3
{ In this case we are going to delay a little the development of the b1-knight since we will adopt a Maroczy-type structure in a great number of situations. }
5... Qc7 { Controlling e5 and keeping the flexibility. } 6. O-O
{ Again keeping all our flexibility intact. } 6... Nf6 7. Qe2
{ With the idea of going for a quick e5 to force Black to play ...d6. This way, the bishop on f8 has to stay on a more passive square. }
7... d6 8. c4
{ Gaining a bit of extra space and finding good squares for our pieces. } 8...
g6
{ The main move. However, the engine considers that this move is quite worse than ...Be7. The reason is that the bishop will be more acive on g7, but at the cost of leaving the d6-pawn weak. }
9. Nc3 Bg7 10. Be3
{ What I like the most of our setup is the facility we have to complete the development and get a good advantage. }
10... O-O 11. Rfd1
{ Bringing this rook here to point at the d6-pawn apuntando a d6 and the other one to c1 eyeing at Black's queen. }
11... Nbd7
{ 11...b6  12.f3  Bb7  13.Rac1  Nbd7  .   11...Nc6  12.Rac1  again, aiming for the same setup. We have a very comfortable position. }
12. Rac1 b6
{ 12...Ne5  13.h3!?  Nxd3  14.Qxd3  and the d6-pawn will suffer a lot. } 13. f3
{ Pre-empting the arrival of Black's light-squared bishop to b7. Now we have to clear the d-file in order to exert pressure on the d6-pawn. }
13... Bb7 14. Qd2 Rac8 15. Bf1
{ This is our standard setup. We will play b4-a3 next, gaining even more space and squeezing Black little by little. }
