1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Kan Sicilian, one of the favorites of Grandmasters in Open tournaments to play for a win against inferior opponents thanks to the great unbalance it creates.   I myself have used c4 against this variation on many occasions. However, I consider that the most recent theory has shown that Black has good chances to get quite close to equality by means of concrete lines focused on a fast break on d5. }
5. Bd3
{ In this case we are going to delay a little the development of the b1-knight since we will adopt a Maroczy-type structure in a great number of situations. }
5... Bc5
{ Dubov's favorite move -and probably the best one objectively speaking. Black wants to develop their dark-squared bishop to a more active square. }
6. Nb3 Be7
{ An attempt to drive the position to Hedgehog territory, but with White's knight on b3, which does not change things as much. }
7. O-O
{ Keeping our flexibility. WE want to include Qg4 to force ...g6 as this move will weaken Black's position. }
7... Nc6
{ Blacks idea is to sacrifice the g7-pawn after our Qg4 by playing Nf6, creating some counterplay. We are going to exploit the fact that the knight is not well placed on c6 in Hedgehog-like type of positions to set up the Maroczy Bind directly. }
8. c4
{ ATaking advantage of the fact that the knight is not usually well placed in the c6-square in Hedgehog positions. That's why we go for them straight away. }
8... Nf6 9. f4 { Prophylacis against d5. } 9... d6
{ 9...d5  10.e5!  the key! Black has no good squares and we keep on gaining more space. }
10. Nc3 O-O 11. Be3
{ The c6-knight hinder Black's pieces @@StartBracket@@it blocks the c-file and the white-squared long diagonal@@EndBracket@@. }
*

