8. Be3 O-O { Black keeps its flexibility with the d-pawn. } 9. Bxa7 Rxa7 10.
Qe3
{ The most concrete move, putting immediate pressure on the rook to improve the queen's position and forcing the knight to the c6-square. This way when b4 comes in the future we can do Na4 without worrying about ...Bd7. @@StartBracket@@example line@@EndBracket@@.   10.Nc3?!  the line could go like this if we go for this innacurate move order wanting to castle queenside.  10...b5  11.Qe3  Rb7!  12.O-O-O?!  b4!  13.Na4  d6!  . }
10... Nbc6
{ 10...Ra8  Black loses time unnecesarily.  11.Nc3  going for the same plan but Black's counterplay is slower. }
11. Nc3 { Going for O-O-O. } 11... b5
{ If  11...e5  12.O-O-O  d6  13.g3  we prepare f4 with a nice pressure on the center. }
12. O-O-O d5
{ 12...Rc7  13.f4  continuing our advance on the kingside.   12...b4  13.Na4  now that the plan with ...Bd7 is not possible, ethe knight is amazingly placed here. Black has no counterplay whatsoever while we will go f4 next. }
13. exd5 exd5 14. Ne2 { Black's isolated pawn is under control. } *

