1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6
{ Black tries a different move order. As BLack has not develop teh knight to f6, our plan with g4 is less strong. }
6. g4
{ We do not care! eThis move is intended as a prophylaxis against Cf6 and we start to gain some space. }
6... a6 { 6...Nge7  7.Be3  a6  .   6...h6  7.Be3  Nf6  8.Rg1  . } 7. Be3
{ Continuing our development. } 7... Nge7
{ Black's plan is to trade on d4 followed by bringing the other knight to c6 and continue with b5. This is pretty logical, as after g5 the knight on f6 would be in a bad situation.   7...Bd7  8.h4  followed by g5; Black's queenside development is quite slow. }
8. f4
{ Gaining a bit of space and, at the same time, controlling important squares. }
8... b5
{ Going for a quick expansion on the queenside, but neglecting the development. }
9. h4
{ As we have already learned, in these positions where there is tension between the knights in the center, we usually let Black take on d4. To make the most of this, we delay the development of our queen to be able to capture on d4 in just one move with Qxd4. }
9... Nxd4
{ If  9...b4  10.Nxc6  Nxc6  11.Na4  The counterplay on the queenside has been frozen and we now go for g5.   9...Bd7  10.a3  stopping Black's ...b4 and we continue with our g5. }
10. Qxd4 { The key move, developing our queen in just one tempo. } 10... Nc6
11. Qd2 { Following our typical plan with g5, Bg2, etc. } *

