{ The simplest move,with the idea of improving our king safety and to attack d6 as well. }
13... Ng6 14. Bxd6 Bxd6 15. Rxd6 { White has a huge advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Scheveningen"]
[Black "5...d6 6.g4 with 7.Be3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6
{ Entering the Sicilian Scheveningen. Black controls the e5-push and prepares a future queenside expansion. }
6. g4
{ As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the drawback of ...d6 by Black is that it is not possible to play the only pawn break available -...d5- in one move. We also take advantage that, unlike in the Najdorf, now we can make g4 indeed, since the bishop on c8 does not control g4 due to the fact that there is a pawn on e6.    Given the rasons above, my recommendation is to play g4 at this point. Black's best plan in most cases is to break with ...d5 at some point, but with the ...d6-tempo down. }
6... e5
{ A very direct move. The drawback is that it weakens the surrounding light squares. }
7. Nf5 h5
{ 7...Nc6  8.Bg5  Seguimos con el desarrollo natural de piezas y buscamos controlar la casilla d5 rapidamente ademas del desarrollo de la dama via d3 o f3, desde c6 el caballo no controla casillas importantes.   7...g6  8.Ne3  tenemos los caballos perfectamente colocados para el control de d5 y la capacidad de seguir rápidamente con g5 para eliminar al único defensor de esa casilla. }
8. Bg5 { We keep developing our pieces aiming to fight for the light squares. }
8... hxg4 9. Nd5 Bxf5
{ 9...Be6  10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.Qxg4  we have two strong knights and, besides, Black's king is in the center, which is too much for our opponent to handle. }
10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. exf5 Bh6
{ The idea is following with ...Bg5, then bring the king to g7 via f8 and support the pawn with a move like ...Rh4. The key plan for us here is to prevent Black's setup.   11...Nc6?!  12.c3!  controlling the black knight's key squares.  12...Bh6  13.Qxg4  . }
12. h4
{ Preventing BLack to build a solid setup and uncoordinating their pieces. }
12... gxh3
{ If  12...Kf8  13.Rg1  we recapture on g4 with the rook to activate one more piece.   12...Nc6  13.Bg2  Our idea is going for the same plan; c3 will come next followed by an eventual capture on g4. Black lacks stability as we have prevented ...Bg5. }
13. Rxh3 Kf8 14. Qf3
{ White has a dominant position thanks to the pin on the h-file. Bd3 and c3 are coming next. }
*

