1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6
{ Entering the Sicilian Scheveningen. Black controls the e5-push and prepares a future queenside expansion. }
6. g4
{ As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the drawback of ...d6 by Black is that it is not possible to play the only pawn break available -...d5- in one move. We also take advantage that, unlike in the Najdorf, now we can make g4 indeed, since the bishop on c8 does not control g4 due to the fact that there is a pawn on e6.    Given the rasons above, my recommendation is to play g4 at this point. Black's best plan in most cases is to break with ...d5 at some point, but with the ...d6-tempo down. }
6... h6
{ Black should not allow g5. The problem of this move is that In the long term it will be difficult for Black to castle short since there is a break point on the g5-square, which will make it very easy for us to access to our opponent's castling. }
7. Rg1
{ Defending quickly the g4-pawn to prevent tactical tricks and preparing an eventual break on g5. This rook move is also useful in some lines, where White can play Bg2 after Black's pawn break on d5 and the subsequent trades. }
7... Nc6 { 7...Be7  8.Be3  Nc6  . } 8. Be3 Be7 9. a3
{ The quintessential move of the course! Once again, this waiting move is very useful, as Black has to decide how to arrange their pieces.   ...O-O would be too risky, as we have the attack well prepared; ...Bd7 would reduce the strength of the d5-break; and the natural a6 is a mistake, as we are going to see. }
9... Bd7 10. Be2
{ We continue to develop calmly. The idea is to defend g4 and prepare h4. }
10... d5
{ The best move, but here the problem with Bd7 is highlighted: now Black has to accept playing with an isolated pawn.   10...a6  11.Qd2  slow and steady improving our position. h4 is on the menu. }
11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Qd2
{ With a comfortable position against Black's isolated pawn. Our idea is to go O-O-O. }
*

