[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6
{ Entering the Sicilian Scheveningen. Black controls the e5-push and prepares a future queenside expansion. }
6. g4
{ As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the drawback of ...d6 by Black is that it is not possible to play the only pawn break available -...d5- in one move. We also take advantage that, unlike in the Najdorf, now we can make g4 indeed, since the bishop on c8 does not control g4 due to the fact that there is a pawn on e6.    Given the rasons above, my recommendation is to play g4 at this point. Black's best plan in most cases is to break with ...d5 at some point, but with the ...d6-tempo down. }
6... h6
{ Black should not allow g5. The problem of this move is that In the long term it will be difficult for Black to castle short since there is a break point on the g5-square, which will make it very easy for us to access to our opponent's castling. }
7. Rg1
{ Defending quickly the g4-pawn to prevent tactical tricks and preparing an eventual break on g5. This rook move is also useful in some lines, where White can play Bg2 after Black's pawn break on d5 and the subsequent trades. }
7... Nc6 { 7...Be7  8.Be3  Nc6  . } 8. Be3 Be7 9. a3
{ The quintessential move of the course! Once again, this waiting move is very useful, as Black has to decide how to arrange their pieces.   ...O-O would be too risky, as we have the attack well prepared; ...Bd7 would reduce the strength of the d5-break; and the natural a6 is a mistake, as we are going to see. }
9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4 e5 11. Qa4+ Bd7 12. Bb5 a6 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7
{ This position exists with the pawn on a2 and it is already better for White. The pawn on a3 helps a lot since it will save us a tempo in many lines after a possible ...b5 by Black, as well as giving an escape route to the king via a2. }
14. Qb3
{ The most direct move, sacrificing our pawn on g4 in exchange for keeping the queens on the board. Black should accept the pawn, otherwise their position would be quite ugly due to the weak light squares in our opponent's camp. }
14... Nxg4 { 14...b5  15.O-O-O  . } 15. Bd2
{ Calm play. In exchange for the pawn, the g file has been opened and this means that the Black king does not have a good square. After Cd5 the queen will be able to swing over through the 3rd rank.   15.Nd5!?  is also goof, but it creates unnecesary complications. }
15... Bh4
{ 15...Rc8  16.h3  Nf6  17.Rxg7  the king on e8 is helpless; we will continue with O-O-O next.   Si  15...O-O  16.Nd5  . }
16. O-O-O { We give another pawn in exchange for speeding up our development. }
16... Bxf2
{ 16...Nxf2  17.Rdf1  and g7 is under attack. After moves such as Be1 and Nd5, Black is not even close to defend. }
17. Rg2 Bd4
{ 17...Bh4  18.Nd5  again, all the pieces are getting closer to Black's king. Nb6 is a real threat and Rdg1 with the idea of Rxg7 is also decisive.   17...Bc5  18.Rf1  with Nd5 coming next and again, all the pieces are getting to the attack. }
18. Nd5
{ THe most direct move.   18.Ne2!?  gives also certain advantage, but if BLsck p`lays precisely, the position can be simplified enough to get anything. }
18... Nf6 { 18...O-O  19.h3  . } 19. Rxg7 Nxd5 20. Qxd5 Kf8
{ Black has to accept to play with the king in this suspicious square.   20...O-O-O  21.Rf1  entering on f7 and finishing off the game. }
21. Rg3 Qc6
{ Obviously, due to the king's situation, Black wishes to exchange queens. }
22. Qb3
{ We have more than compensation for the pawn thanks to the disastrous position of Black's king on f8. }
*

