[Black "2...e6 with 4.Nxd4 Qb6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ In this chapter we will have a look at some Black sidelines that BLack has at their disposal in this position. Objectively, they are not dangerous for us, but it is important to know them because they contain some hidden traps. }
4... Qb6
{ I myself have used this line many years ago and I can assure you that if White is not careful it is very easy to get better with Black very quickly. The idea is the same as ...Bc5 but putting direct pressure on b2 to hinder the development of our c1-bishop. }
5. Be3
{ Going for a quick piece development, sacrificing the b2-pawn in exchange of counterplay and a huge advantage in development. }
5... a6 { 5...Bc5  . } 6. a3
{ I really like this move because it hides several tricks besides being very useful. We want to continue with Nc3 without allowing Qxb2 because of Na4. Qxb2 looks tempting now, but.... }
6... Qxb2 7. Nxe6 { The threats are Bd4 trapping the queen and also Nc7. } 7...
Qxa1 { 7...dxe6  8.Bd4  and Black's queen is trapped. } 8. Nc7+ Kd8 9. Nxa8
{ And oddly enough there is material parity, but we are winning because we have pieces playing and an attacking objective that cannot be hidden. }
