1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ In this chapter we will have a look at some Black sidelines that BLack has at their disposal in this position. Objectively, they are not dangerous for us, but it is important to know them because they contain some hidden traps. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Qb6
{ A tricky -and important to know!- variation.   5...a6?  6.e5!  Black should react somehow to prevent this.  6...Ng8  7.Bf4  and White has good development without giving anything in return for it. }
6. e5 { The move that we almost always play if Black allows it. } 6... Nd5 7.
Nxd5 exd5 8. Nb3
{ Here are several possible good moves, and this is the simplest of them all, preventing ...Bc5 and quickly going for the d5-pawn. }
8... Qe6 { 8...Nc6  9.Qxd5  . } 9. Be3
{ Continuing our development, Black has only developed the queen. } 9... Nc6
10. Qd2 { After O-O-O, we will take on d5 with a very superior endgame. } *

