1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ In this chapter we will have a look at some Black sidelines that BLack has at their disposal in this position. Objectively, they are not dangerous for us, but it is important to know them because they contain some hidden traps. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ The so called Pin Variation of the Sicilian, a line that Jobava has played quite a lot recently.  You have to be careful and prepared to play some strange positions.   5...Bc5  6.e5  Qb6  . }
6. e5 Ne4 { The most direct move, preventing the Bd2 line, but... } 7. Qg4 Qa5
8. Qxg7 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qxc3+ 10. Ke2
{ This way we prevent Black from taking our knight with check. } 10... b6
{ If  10...Nc6  11.Qxh8+  Ke7  12.Nb3  BLack's attack goes nowhere. } 11. Qxh8+
Ke7 12. Ba3+ d6
{ 12...Qxa3  13.Qxc8  Now that we prevented the check on a6, our material advantge is decisivea. }
13. Nb3 { Controlling d2 and defending the rook. } 13... Ba6+ 14. Kd1 Nxf2+ 15.
Kc1 { The rook is immune due to exd6+ and the queen falls. } *

