1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ In this chapter we will have a look at some Black sidelines that BLack has at their disposal in this position. Objectively, they are not dangerous for us, but it is important to know them because they contain some hidden traps. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ The so called Pin Variation of the Sicilian, a line that Jobava has played quite a lot recently.  You have to be careful and prepared to play some strange positions.   5...Bc5  6.e5  Qb6  . }
6. e5 Ne4 { The most direct move, preventing the Bd2 line, but... } 7. Qg4 Nxc3
8. Qxg7 Rf8 { 8...Ne4+  9.c3  . } 9. a3
{ The bishop has to decide whether to defend the knight or the rook. } 9... Qa5
10. axb4 { Going into a completely forcing line. } 10... Qxa1 11. Nb3 Qb1 12.
bxc3 Qxc2 13. Bh6 Qxc3+ 14. Nd2 Qxb4 15. Be2
{ Black can barely move. Our simple plan is to castle and bring our pieces closer to Black's king. }
15... Nc6 16. O-O { Ne4 comes next, deciding the game in our favor. } *

