1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ In this chapter we will have a look at some Black sidelines that BLack has at their disposal in this position. Objectively, they are not dangerous for us, but it is important to know them because they contain some hidden traps. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ The so called Pin Variation of the Sicilian, a line that Jobava has played quite a lot recently.  You have to be careful and prepared to play some strange positions.   5...Bc5  6.e5  Qb6  . }
6. e5 Nd5 7. Bd2 { Forcing Black to make a decision. } 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3
{ Despite the momentarily worse structure, we have a great amount of extra development tempi in return. }
8... Ba5
{ This leaves the dark squares on the kingside very weak.   Si  8...Bf8  9.Bd3!  it is not necessary to complicate your life too much, you only have to see that Black does not have a single piece out.  9...d6  10.Qe2  followed by O-O. We will bring our rooks to the center next, Black is too far behind in development.   9...Na6  . }
9. Qg4 O-O
{ 9...g6  10.Nb5  .   9...Kf8  10.h4  from h3 the rook will defend c3 nullifying the only usefulness of the bishop on a5 and we continue with the attack. }
10. Bd3 d6 11. Nf3 dxe5
{ 11...f5  12.exf6  Rxf6  13.Ng5  All of our pieces are attacking!   11...g6  12.h4  intending to go h5 next and, with this pawn break, the rook joins the party. }
12. Bxh7+ Kxh7 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Ng5 { The greek gift! } *

