1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ After this move we enter directly in the Accelerated Dragon. In return of giving up the center, Black will have a solid control of the central dark squares. }
5. c4
{ Going into a Maroczy Bind structure. White gains space in the center and takes advantage of it. We have to be a bit careful on the next moves, as Black may have some tactical tricks at their disposal. }
5... Nf6
{ One of the trickiest move orders. The f6-knight has the chance of jumping to g4 in some lines. }
6. Nc3 d6
{ This seemingly harmless order hides a very annoying threat: now the bishop controls g4 and, therefore, the knight jump becomes a reality.   6...Bg7  7.Be3  . }
7. Be2
{ Controlling g4 and transposing to the main line.   7.Be3?  Don't fall into this trap!!  7...Ng4  Black wins our dark-squared bishop and, with it, they will completely dominate this color complex. }
7... Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 { Transposing to the main move order. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Accelerated Dragon"]
[Black "4...g6 with 6...Nxd4 7.Qxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ After this move we enter directly in the Accelerated Dragon. In return of giving up the center, Black will have a solid control of the central dark squares. }
5. c4
{ Going into a Maroczy Bind structure. White gains space in the center and takes advantage of it. We have to be a bit careful on the next moves, as Black may have some tactical tricks at their disposal. }
5... Nf6
{ One of the trickiest move orders. The f6-knight has the chance of jumping to g4 in some lines. }
6. Nc3 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 d6
{ It is important to control the e5-square.   If  7...Bg7?  8.e5!  and the knight has no good squares to go to and has to return home.  8...Ng8  9.Bf4  cwith a huge development advantage for White. This is a good example of what can happen to Black if they are not careful with the e5 advance in this type of positions. }
8. Be3 { We keep on developing our pieces in a standard way. } 8... Bg7 9. Be2
{ Controlling g4 and getting ready to castle on the kingside. } 9... O-O
{ After  9...Qa5   Not  10.Qd3?  -we have to be on the lookout!-  10...Nxe4!  10.O-O  O-O  11.Qd3!  suddenly, all Black's pieces coordinate perfectly. This trap is very typical and we have to be a bit careful. }
10. Qd3
{ A trendy move. From d3 we defend e4 more effectively, as we do not weaken our position with f3 and our plan will be faster than Black's to carry out. }
10... a5
{ One of the most typical plans in this type of position; Black tries to gain some space on the queenside and, at the same time, stop the possible White expansion with b4. }
11. O-O { Finishing our development before taking further concrete action. }
11... a4
{ Si  11...Bd7  12.b3!  This way we are prepared to reply to a4 with b4 without opening the a-file @@StartBracket@@this way we avoid piece exchanges, which favors us considering our space advantage@@EndBRacket@@ and the black queen will not get the powerful a5-square.  12...a4  13.b4  . }
12. Bd4 { Playing in the center and preparing f4. } 12... Be6 13. f4 Qa5 14.
Rad1
{ Removing the rook from a1 to be able to play b3 without allowing Black to go ...Qxa1. }
14... Rfc8 15. b3 { Black's counterplay is under control and now comes ours. }
