[White "9) Accelerated Dragon"]
[Black "4...g6 with 5...Bg7 6.Be3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ After this move we enter directly in the Accelerated Dragon. In return of giving up the center, Black will have a solid control of the central dark squares. }
5. c4
{ Going into a Maroczy Bind structure. White gains space in the center and takes advantage of it. We have to be a bit careful on the next moves, as Black may have some tactical tricks at their disposal. }
5... Bg7 6. Be3
{ It is important to not take on c6 because this will help Black's development. Although the b2-pawn is hanging -which can be scary-, Black has no way of exploiting it. }
6... d6
{ A slightly dangerous move order. The best that black can do is to end up transposing }
7. Nc3 Qb6
{ 7...Nh6?  8.h3!  imagine how bad ...Nh6 must be if the engine here recommends ...Ng8.  8...f5  9.exf5  Nxf5  10.Nxf5  Bxf5  11.Rc1  Black has created many weaknesses in exchange for nothing.   7...Nf6  . }
8. Ndb5 Bxc3+
{ This is the attempt to justify this idea, but it is bad because of the weaknesses on dark squares that it leaves.   8...Qa5  9.Bd2  . }
9. Nxc3 Qxb2 10. Nb5 Kf8
{ 10...Rb8  11.Rb1  Qe5  12.Bd3  our bishop pair and the open long diagonal is too much for Black to handle. }
11. Be2
{ There is no need to go crazy; with only one sacrificed pawn we have a lot of compensation. }
11... Nf6 { 11...Kg7  12.Bd2  . } 12. Bh6+ Kg8 13. O-O
{ In exchange for a mere pawn Black can barely move. Now all that remains is to open the position and take advantage of Black's disastrous coordination. }
