[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Accelerated Dragon"]
[Black "4...g6 with 5...Bg7 6.Be3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ After this move we enter directly in the Accelerated Dragon. In return of giving up the center, Black will have a solid control of the central dark squares. }
5. c4
{ Going into a Maroczy Bind structure. White gains space in the center and takes advantage of it. We have to be a bit careful on the next moves, as Black may have some tactical tricks at their disposal. }
5... Bg7 6. Be3
{ It is important to not take on c6 because this will help Black's development. Although the b2-pawn is hanging -which can be scary-, Black has no way of exploiting it. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 Ng4
{ An old line. Black aims to trade some pieces, but keeping more contro, of the dark squares. The problem is that the c6-knight will will disrupt Black's own pieces even more. }
8. Qxg4 Nxd4 9. Qd1 e5
{ This move creates so many long-term weaknessesin exchange for a square which we can recover. }
10. Bd3 { Momentarily ignoring the knight, we continue our development. } 10...
O-O 11. O-O d6 12. Qd2
{ Now we have finished developing our pieces, our plan now is to keep BLack's pawn breaks under control @@StartBracket@@especially ...b5@@EndBracket@@ and prepare Ne2 to eliminate Black's strong knight so we can put pressure on Black's d6-weakness in the future. }
12... f5
{ Black's typical counterplay, but it is usually quite bad due to the lot of weaknesses in our opponent's camp. }
13. exf5 gxf5
{ If Black takes with a piece after  13...Bxf5  14.Rad1  their position is full of holes that cannot be justified. Taking with the pawn on f5 at least gives them some extra space. }
14. Bxd4 exd4 15. Nd5
{ The weaknesses on the light squares and the bad structure makes this position a nightmare for BLack to play and hold. }
