[Black "6...bxc6 7.e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. e5
{ Kicking Black's knight and forcing it to go home again. } 7... Ng8
{ The most played move by far, but it is bad.Black cannot justify the lack of development if we play accurately. }
8. Qf3 { Putting pressure on f7 and c6 to hinder Black's development. } 8...
Bg7
{ It seems the most logical, looking for quick counterplay attacking our e5-pawn. }
9. Bc4 f5
{ 9...e6  creates quite a lot of weaknesses that our knight will take advantage of.  10.Bf4  Ne7  11.Ne4  and Black's position is a sieve.   10...Qa5  . }
10. Bf4
{ We continue our rapid development, in this case getting ready for O-O-O. }
10... e6 { Giving the e7-square to the knight.   10...Qa5  . } 11. O-O-O Qc7
{ Black relies on the pressure against e5 to justify their position, but we can even ignore it and look for a quick counterplay. }
12. h4 Nh6
{ 12...Bxe5  seems tempting, but we have a beautiful tactical resource.  13.Bxe5  Qxe5  14.Bxe6  the bishop is taboo either due to the pin or to the capture on c6. }
13. h5 g5
{ Si  13...Nf7  14.hxg6  hxg6  15.Qg3  g6 falls and, with it, the position as well. }
14. Bxg5 Nf7 { 14...Qxe5  15.Bxe6  . } 15. Bf4
{ Black's lack of development and weak king are fatal. } *

