[White "10) A dubious move order to avoid the Maroczy Bind"]
[Black "6...bxc6 7.e5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. e5
{ Kicking Black's knight and forcing it to go home again. } 7... Nh5
{ The best attempt for Black. } 8. Bc4 Qa5
{ I think it is not necessary to explain why  8...Ng7  is a bad move.  9.O-O  Ne6  10.Be3  with a huge advantage in development for White. }
9. f4
{ 9.O-O  is also good, sbut I do not see why we should complicate the game unnecesarily having a simpler move at our disposal which can give us advantage as well. }
9... Ba6
{ 9...Rb8  10.Qe2  defending the bishop to continue with O-O without allowing ...Qc5. }
10. Bxa6 Qxa6 11. Be3 { Black's pieces have little prospect. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Hyper Accelerated Dragon"]
[Black "2...g6 3.d4 with 5.Bxa6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6
{ This is the Hyper-Accelerated Dragon. The main advantage of this move order for Black is that is to avoid some sidelines like the Rossolimo @@StartBracket@@3.Bb5 after 2...Nc6@@EndBracket@@. As we are going to play the Open Sicilian, our line will transpose to the standard Accelerated Dragon in most cases. }
3. d4 Bg7
{ A dubious idea, but we have to be careful not to be catched offguard.   3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Bg7  5.c4  transposing to the Accelerated Dragon. }
4. dxc5
{ Accepting the treat. If Black wants to get the pawn back, they should be quick at the cost of leaving their queen exposed. }
4... Na6 5. Bxa6
{ Removing the attacker of our c5-pawn and, at the same time, developing our pieces aggressively. }
5... bxa6 6. Qd5
{ Very concrete move, taking advantage of our opponent's weaknesses. } 6... Rb8
7. Ne5 e6 8. Qd6
{ We have managed to improve the position of our pieces and also to create serious weaknesses on the dark squares. }
*

