[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3
{ Controlling g4 to prevent knight jumps there and, besides, aiming to play for the g4-push ourselves. }
7... Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O
{ 8...Bd7?!  is inaccurate, as the queen does not put pressure anymore along the d-file. Therefore, it is not necessary to  to be so aware of the d5-break and, for that reason, we can skip the move Ac4.  9.g4  O-O  10.O-O-O  .   8...d5?  9.Bb5!  Bd7  10.Nxd5  . }
9. Bc4
{ This move is important because it controls d5. In addition, the bishop can serve as a defensive piece once we bring it to b3. }
9... Nd7
{ A very old line. Black maneuvers with the knights to try to gain quick access to the c4-square. The problem with this is that Black's castling without the knight on f6 is barely holding and the c4-square can be covered with b3. }
10. h4
{ Directly to the neck, taking advantage of the fact that the knight does not control h5 anymore. }
10... Nb6 11. Be2
{ The simplest move, with the idea of covering the c4-square very easily: simply playing b3. }
11... d5
{ It does not make much sense to change the plan now since the knight on b6 exerts less pressure on the center than on f6. }
12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. O-O-O
{ We will continue with moves like h5 and Bh6 going for the typical attack. The knight on b6, far from attacking, blocks the file and possible ...Qa5 ideas. }
