1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3
{ Controlling g4 to prevent knight jumps there and, besides, aiming to play for the g4-push ourselves. }
7... Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O
{ 8...Bd7?!  is inaccurate, as the queen does not put pressure anymore along the d-file. Therefore, it is not necessary to  to be so aware of the d5-break and, for that reason, we can skip the move Ac4.  9.g4  O-O  10.O-O-O  .   8...d5?  9.Bb5!  Bd7  10.Nxd5  . }
9. Bc4
{ This move is important because it controls d5. In addition, the bishop can serve as a defensive piece once we bring it to b3. }
9... Nxd4
{ This is Giri's recommdnation. Black wants to exchange some pieces to reduce White's eventual attack. }
10. Bxd4 Be6 11. Bxe6
{ Worsening Black's structure and continuing with the development, our plan will be to prepare the e5-push. }
11... fxe6 12. O-O-O Qa5 13. Rhe1
{ The key move. We want to go e5 quickly to force Black to play ...Nd7. } 13...
Nd7
{ 13...e5?!  This condemns the g7-bishop forever and, consequently, Black's attack will never be a success.  14.Be3  . }
14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. e5
{ Very direct, exploiting our better piece activity to break in the center. }
15... d5
{ Black has to keep the center closed. Although it is true that there is some counterplay, I think that the endgame in general is much more comfortable for White. }
16. a3
{ The quieter move, intending to go Ne2, which lwads to a slightly favorable endgame for White thanks to nour better pawn structure and the strong d4-square.   16.Re3  Nb6  17.b3  . }
16... Rac8 17. Ne2 Qxd2+ 18. Rxd2
{ Nd4 comes next, followed by creating a solid kingside by putting our pawns on f4+g3+h4 }
