[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3
{ Controlling g4 to prevent knight jumps there and, besides, aiming to play for the g4-push ourselves. }
7... Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O
{ 8...Bd7?!  is inaccurate, as the queen does not put pressure anymore along the d-file. Therefore, it is not necessary to  to be so aware of the d5-break and, for that reason, we can skip the move Ac4.  9.g4  O-O  10.O-O-O  .   8...d5?  9.Bb5!  Bd7  10.Nxd5  . }
9. Bc4
{ This move is important because it controls d5. In addition, the bishop can serve as a defensive piece once we bring it to b3. }
9... Bd7
{ The main line. Black continues their development and makes room for the rook to get to c8. }
10. O-O-O
{ In this case we finish our development before taking further action. Now Black can play in many different ways, but our plan is usually very similar: we will attack by means of a pawn storm on the kingside and, as a defensive resource, we will put our king on b1. }
10... Qa5
{ This plan is not dangerous in my opinion. I think that ...Qa5 should be played in combination with ...Nxd4 and bringing the bishop to e6. The bishop on d7 is not well placed. }
11. Kb1 Rfc8 12. Bb3
{ Completing our standard defensive setup before taking further action. } 12...
Ne5 13. h4 { Let's start our counterplay! } 13... h5
{ This is usually the way in which Black stops our attack and can lead to very crazy positions when we look for g4, sacrificing the pawn. In this case, Black is very well prepared for this advance so we are going to continue with our attack in a different way. }
14. Bg5
{ Intending to take on f6 followed by Nd5 with the idea of ruining BLack's pawn structure. }
14... Nc4
{ 14...Rxc3!?  15.Qxc3  Qxc3  16.bxc3  Black has some compensation, but far from enough. We will continue by centralizing our pieces and open files with move such as Rhe1+f4+e5. }
15. Bxc4 Rxc4 16. Bxf6
{ The key move, exploiting the fact that the queen is undefended on a5. } 16...
Bxf6
{ 16...exf6  17.Nb3  Qe5  18.Qxd6  reaching a comfortable endgame with an extra pawn for us. Besides, we have the control over some strong central squares for our knights. }
17. Nd5 Qxd2 18. Nxf6+ exf6 { 18...Kg7  19.Nxh5+  . } 19. Rxd2
{ Black's structure is horrendous. } *

