[Round "?"]
[White "12) Classical Dragon"]
[Black "5...g6 6.Be3, 7.f3 with 8.Qd2 and 9...Bd7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3
{ Controlling g4 to prevent knight jumps there and, besides, aiming to play for the g4-push ourselves. }
7... Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O
{ 8...Bd7?!  is inaccurate, as the queen does not put pressure anymore along the d-file. Therefore, it is not necessary to  to be so aware of the d5-break and, for that reason, we can skip the move Ac4.  9.g4  O-O  10.O-O-O  .   8...d5?  9.Bb5!  Bd7  10.Nxd5  . }
9. Bc4
{ This move is important because it controls d5. In addition, the bishop can serve as a defensive piece once we bring it to b3. }
9... Bd7
{ The main line. Black continues their development and makes room for the rook to get to c8. }
10. O-O-O
{ In this case we finish our development before taking further action. Now Black can play in many different ways, but our plan is usually very similar: we will attack by means of a pawn storm on the kingside and, as a defensive resource, we will put our king on b1. }
10... Ne5 11. Be2
{ From e2 we make the b5-push more difficult and we can make g4 in better conditions in the future, as ...d5 by BLack is not an option anymore; the bishop has already accomplished its mission on c4. }
11... Rc8 { 11...Qa5  12.Nb3  Qc7  13.g4  continuing with the attack. } 12. Kb1
{ Improving our position to the max before taking further action. } 12... Nc4
{ 12...a6  13.g4  b5  14.h4  with the typical opposite-side castling battle in which we are faster. }
13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. g4
{ This way we definitely prevent ...h5.   14.h4?!  h5  BLack is very well prepared to stop our attack, so we have to be very careful. }
14... b5
{ 14...a6?!  is so slow and unnecesary.  15.h4  h5  16.gxh5!  cracking the position open  16...Nxh5  17.Rhg1  plans with Rg5, f4+f5 or the simple Nde2+Bd4 are possible.   If  15...b5  16.h5  .   If  14...Qa5  15.g5!  this is not usual, but here this move order is justified thanks to the huge amount of tempi we gain.  15...Nh5  16.Nd5  Qd8  17.Ne2  freeing the d-file to exert pressure quickly on d6 in case Black plays ...e6 and also to prepare Ng3. Bxa7 is also a threat. }
15. g5 Nh5 { 15...b4  16.gxf6  bxc3  17.Qd3  . } 16. b3
{ Kicking the rook away to a passive square. } 16... b4
{ 16...Rc8  17.Ndxb5  Qa5  18.Nd5  If Black takes on b5 we would play Nxe7 and later on we will take the rook and the d6-pawn. If we add to this the fact that the h5-knight is inactive and that we have a light-squared bishop, our position would be completely winning. }
17. Nd5
{ This is the idea behind our move order here. we would reach a very similar position to the main line one after bxc4 where, although white has a huge advantage, in my opinion the position is not as easy to play as it seems. }
17... Rc8 18. Ne2
{ Intending to target Black's weak points and also with the idea of playing Ng3 to keep the attack going. We have complete domination of the dark squares as all our pieces have control of the queenside while Black's h5-knight and d7-bishop are doing nothing. }
18... e6 { 18...Be6  19.Qxb4  . } 19. Nxb4 a5
{ Going into a very concrete line. } 20. Qxd6 axb4 21. Qxd7 Qa5
{ Despite being two pawns down and an inactive knight on h5, Black has some counterplay, so we have to be precise. }
22. Qa7 { If we trade queens, the game will be immediately over. } 22... Qb5
{ 22...Qe5  23.Bd4  removing the dark-squared bishops from the board decreases as well BLack's chances of counterplay. }
23. Rd3 Ra8 24. Qd7 Qe5 25. Bd4
{ Again, we manage to trade the dark-squared bishops, getting an advantage. } *

