{ 8...Bd7?!  is inaccurate, as the queen does not put pressure anymore along the d-file. Therefore, it is not necessary to  to be so aware of the d5-break and, for that reason, we can skip the move Ac4.  9.g4  O-O  10.O-O-O  .   8...d5?  9.Bb5!  Bd7  10.Nxd5  . }
9. Bc4
{ This move is important because it controls d5. In addition, the bishop can serve as a defensive piece once we bring it to b3. }
9... Bd7
{ The main line. Black continues their development and makes room for the rook to get to c8. }
10. O-O-O
{ In this case we finish our development before taking further action. Now Black can play in many different ways, but our plan is usually very similar: we will attack by means of a pawn storm on the kingside and, as a defensive resource, we will put our king on b1. }
10... Rb8 { Black gets ready to push ...b5 in better conditions. } 11. Kb1
{ First things first, let's secure our king a little and prepare to accept Black's possible gift. }
11... Nxd4
{ The most human move, preparing the ...b5-push without losing the pawn.   Si  11...Na5  12.Be2  b5  13.Ndxb5  a6  14.Nd4  . }
12. Bxd4 b5 13. Bf1
{ A surprising move. We do not go with the bishop to b3 because this will make Black's attack faster after ...a5. Also, since our plan is Nd5+exd5, the bishop on b3 would be badly placed. On e2 it would be natural, but we need that square for the knight in some lines. }
13... e6
{ Preventing ...Nd5, but, as usual, the d6-pawn will suffer because of that. }
14. g4 b4 15. Ne2 { That is why it is important to go Bf1. } 15... Qa5 16. g5
Nh5 17. Bxg7 Nxg7 18. h4
{ We will continue with Nf4 with the idea of bringing it to h5. The d6-pawn will suffer. }
