[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3
{ Controlling g4 to prevent knight jumps there and, besides, aiming to play for the g4-push ourselves. }
7... Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O
{ 8...Bd7?!  is inaccurate, as the queen does not put pressure anymore along the d-file. Therefore, it is not necessary to  to be so aware of the d5-break and, for that reason, we can skip the move Ac4.  9.g4  O-O  10.O-O-O  .   8...d5?  9.Bb5!  Bd7  10.Nxd5  . }
9. Bc4
{ This move is important because it controls d5. In addition, the bishop can serve as a defensive piece once we bring it to b3. }
9... Bd7
{ The main line. Black continues their development and makes room for the rook to get to c8. }
10. O-O-O
{ In this case we finish our development before taking further action. Now Black can play in many different ways, but our plan is usually very similar: we will attack by means of a pawn storm on the kingside and, as a defensive resource, we will put our king on b1. }
10... Rc8 11. Nxc6
{ This is the key idea why I wanted to recommend this line, and it has been played in less than 1% of the games that have reached this position and it is not at all easy to find the right reaction from Black as it involves a very different plan from the usual one. }
11... Bxc6 12. Bb3
{ Defending everything and preparing our counterplay. BLack should be very precise with their attack. }
12... a5 13. a4 { Stopping the counterplay on the light squares. } 13... Qe8
{ Black insists of going for the ...b5-push. } 14. Qe2
{ We have won the battle for the b5-push; BLack should bring more pieces if they want to play it. }
14... Nd7 15. h4 Nc5 16. Bxc5
{ Even if it hurts, you have to get rid of the dark-squared bishop, but in this case it is justified because we will encarcelate our opponent's dark-squared bishop. }
16... dxc5 17. e5
{ This pawn stops the Dragon bishop from 'roaring', and we will exploit the fact that we have one more minor piece that dominates the light-squares to completely control this color complex. }
17... e6 18. Bc4
{ Sacrificing the a4-pawm in exchange for a lot of counterplay. If Black does not take it, the position will be very uncomfortable for them after Bb5. }
18... Bxa4 19. h5 Bc6 20. h6 Bh8 21. f4
{ Total domination. The f-pawn is immobile due to e6. We aim for Ne4 and move the g2-pawn to g5, after which we will be playing with an extra piece. }
*

