[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Moussard, J. (2626) vs. Nevednichy, V. (2546) 7th Sunway Sitges 2020"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/1p3ppp/p1np1n2/4p3/2P1P3/1NNBQ3/PP3PPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13. Rfd1
{ Moussard the plan we have already explained begins: simply doubling the rooks to exert pressure on d6. }
13... Be6 14. Be2 { Clearing the way for the rook. } 14... Qb8 15. Rd2 Rd8 16.
Rad1 h6
{ Now that the black pieces are tied up, it is time to improve the position a little more and get ready to open it. }
17. h3 b6 18. Kh2 Ra7 19. g3
{ Preparing f4. If taken, we recapture with the pawn to open the position up and win quite some space. }
19... Kf8 20. f4 exf4 21. gxf4
{ Black is dominated, the only thing left to do is to put pressure on the g-file. }
21... Re7 22. Qg3 b5 { The counterplay is tardy. } 23. Rg1 g6 24. Qh4
{ Bringing more pieces to the kingside. Kg7 looks bad as as it places the king in the rook's sight. }
24... Ng8 25. Nd5 Bxd5 26. cxd5 Na7 27. Bf3
{ All that remains is to prepare the breakthrough on the kingside. } 27... Rde8
28. Nd4 { Bringing the remaining piece. } 28... Qd8 29. Rdg2
{ f5 is next, bringing the point home. } 29... Rd7 30. Qxd8 Rdxd8 31. Ne6+ Ke7
{ 31...fxe6  32.Rxg6  Ke7  33.Rg7++- } 32. Nxd8 Kxd8 33. Rc1
{ White is an exchange up. All we have to do now is to bring the pieces to the c-file. }
33... h5 34. Rgc2 Re7 35. e5 { The fnal blow. } 35... Nh6 36. exd6 Rd7 37. Rc7
Rxc7 38. dxc7+ Kc8 39. d6 Nf5 40. Bb7+
{ Giving way to the b-pawn to finish the game off. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Niemann, H. (2637) vs. Sindarov, J. (2587) FIDE Grand Swiss 2021"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1r3k1/pp2ppbp/3pbnp1/q7/2PBP3/1PNQ4/P3BPPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13... Nd7
{ In the course we recommend Kh1 here, but the move played in the game leads to similar positions. }
14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. f4 { Intending to go f5 trapping the bishop. } 15... f6
{ Necessarfy move to free a square for the bishop and also to control the dark squares, but it creates but it creates permanent weaknesses in Black's position. }
16. Kh1 Qb6 17. Rae1
{ Niemann brings his pieces to their best squares before taking further action. }
17... a5
{ Black desperately tries to create counterplay seeing what is coming, but this weakens the b5-square for the rest of the game. }
18. Qg3
{ Looking to exchange our worst piece with Bg4 to take better advantage of the weakness of d5.   18.Nd5  Bxd5  19.exd5  was another way of playing, and also gives White a nice advantage. }
18... Nc5 19. Bg4 Bxg4 20. Nd5 Qd8 21. Qxg4 e6 22. Nc3
{ White has managed to force Black to play ...e6 with the exchange of the light-squared bishops. Now the d6-pawn is weak. }
22... Qe7 23. Qd1 { The queen regroups to attack Black's weaknesses. } 23... a4
24. Nb5 axb3 25. axb3 Ra6 26. b4 Nd7 27. Qd3
{ Defending c4 and giving way to the rook to put pressure on d6. } 27... e5 28.
f5
{ In this way we deny the square e5 to the d7-knight, which is now blocking the defense of the d6-pawn from the d-file. }
28... Nb8 29. Rd1 Rb6 30. Nc3
{ THe knight heads to d5 to take advantage of the recently created weakness on f6. }
30... Rbc6 31. Nd5 Qe8 32. fxg6 Nd7 33. gxh7 Rxc4 34. Ne3
{ The knight continues to move around the board taking advantage of the weaknesses; now it goes to f5 in order to take on d6. }
34... Rc3 35. Nf5+ Kxh7 36. Qxd6 R8c7 37. Rf3 Rc1 38. Rh3+ Kg6 39. Qd2 Rxd1+
40. Qxd1 { Sindarov resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Anton, D. (2660) vs. Bosiocic, M. (2603) EU-ch Minsk 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this part of the course we will analyze the ...e6-Sicilians, in which Black keeps the flexibility of their piece development, as we are going to see. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ This is one of the most flexible move orders for Black, as it allows them to choose between the Taimanov Sicilian, the Two Knights Sicilian and it allows playing with ...a6 as well. As this move hits the center directly, it is not easy for White to go for a Maroczy Bind structure directly.   At this point I am going to recommend two moves. The first one -our main line- will be Nc3, which is the standard move. Our idea is to develop our pieces and control the center. However, the party is not over yet. The second move I recommend goes specifically against opponents who have the Taimanov as a main weapon, since we are practically going to make life impossible for them.. }
5. Nc3
{ The knight develops naturally and conyrols some central squares. After this move, our chances of going for a Marozcy structure are gone. However, this will not be a problem.   5.a3!  is the other option and will be analyzed in the Two Knights chapter. }
5... Qc7
{ After this move we are in Taimanov Sicilian territory. This is -in my humble opinion- the best Sicilian for Black after the Najdorf and the Sveshnikov. Black usually plays very flexible by combining pawn pushes on both flanks @@StartBracket@@...a6 and ...b5 or ...h5@@EndBracket@@. As Black's queen controls the e5-square, they does not need to play ...d6 in many lines and, as a result, the f8-bishop can be developed to a more aggresive squares such as b4, c5 or even d6 in some cases. }
6. a3
{ This will be my recommendation against the Taimanov. As I did in Play the Sicilian, Part 1, I am going to try to recommend positions with similar pawn structures. This is the reason why we are going to play the move a3 in quite a number of lines. Being less well-known than the main line, this move -played by strong Russian GMs- is the most flexible move by White here and its idea is to pre-empt Black plans with ...a6+...b5 and prevent their dark-squared bishop to get to b4. }
6... Nf6
{ Probably the most natural move for Black to control the central squares and develop a piece. However, this would already be their first mistake. Let's take advantage of this early development of the knight on f6 to quickly look for ideas with f4+e5 to harass Black @@StartBracket@@the move a3 ideally combines with these pawn advances as it prevents the pins on b4@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Be3
{ This move is a direct transposition to one of the main lines of the Taimanov @@StartBracket@@6.Be3@@EndBracket@@. However, the tournament practice has shown that the move ...Nf6 is an innacurate move order for Black due to the aforementioned pawn pushes. We simply develop another piece that helps to control the center and prepare f4 a bit better. }
7... a6
{ The most played move in practice. Black prevents all the annoying jumps to b5 and, at the same time, prepares the ...b5-push. }
8. f4
{ Controlling directly the center and starting to create some very annoying threats -after e5, the f6-knight has no good squares-. We take advantage of the fact that Black is not completely ready to break in the center with ...d5 to force our opponent to play d6 since, after this, they will adopt a more passive position. }
8... d6 9. Qf3
{ Continuing our piece development, exerting indirect pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal. It is important to develop our queen to f3 because this will allow us to castle long very soon and, besides, we keep on having the g4-square under control for an eventual advance of our g-pawn. }
9... Bd7
{ Aiming for a quick queenside development. This move gives room for the rook and prepares an eventual recapture on c6 with the bishop in case White trades there. }
10. O-O-O
{ Following our development. We bring the king to safety and we activate the rook along the d-file. }
10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 { Directly bringing the bishop to its best diagonal. }
11... Bc6 { Model Game } 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. f5 h5 14. Bc4 Bd7 15. fxe6 fxe6 16.
Qxf6 Rh6 17. Qg5 Qc5 18. Bd5 Rh8 19. Qg6+ Ke7 20. Kb1 Qe3 21. Bxe6 Bxe6 22.
Nd5+ Bxd5 23. exd5 Rh6 24. Qg8 Kd7 25. Rde1
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@25@@EndBracket@@ Anton Guijarro,D @@StartBracket@@2660@@EndBracket@@-Bosiocic,M @@StartBracket@@2603@@EndBracket@@ Minsk 2017 CBM 179 @@StartSquare@@Moradiabadi,E@@EndSquare@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Santos, M (2605) vs. Abalia, A (2193) San Cristóbal Open"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ After this move we enter directly in the Accelerated Dragon. In return of giving up the center, Black will have a solid control of the central dark squares. }
5. c4
{ Going into a Maroczy Bind structure. White gains space in the center and takes advantage of it. We have to be a bit careful on the next moves, as Black may have some tactical tricks at their disposal. }
5... Bg7 6. Be3
{ It is important to not take on c6 because this will help Black's development. Although the b2-pawn is hanging -which can be scary-, Black has no way of exploiting it. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 Ng4
{ An old line. Black aims to trade some pieces, but keeping more contro, of the dark squares. The problem is that the c6-knight will will disrupt Black's own pieces even more. }
8. Qxg4 Nxd4 9. Qd1 Ne6 10. Rc1
{ Preventing Black from permanently doubling our pawns. } 10... Qa5 11. f4
{ Keeping the flexibility with the development of the f1-bishop. In case black plays ...b6 we put it on d3 to hold e4, otherwise on e2 it is well placed. }
11... d6 12. Be2 b6 { 12...O-O  13.O-O  . } 13. O-O Bb7 14. Nd5 Bxb2 15. Rb1
Bg7 16. f5 Bxd5 17. cxd5 Nc5 18. Bb5+ Kf8 19. f6 Bxf6 20. Bh6+ Bg7 21. Qd4 e5
22. dxe6 Nxe6 23. Qf6 Kg8 24. Qxf7#
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Santos Ruiz, M @@StartBracket@@2605@@EndBracket@@- Abalia Patino, A @@StartBracket@@2193@@EndBracket@@ San Cristóbal de la Laguna 2021 }
